{"title_page": "Cornel West", "text_new": "{{short description|African-American philosopher and political/civil rights activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{for|the residential section of Cornell University|Cornell West Campus}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Cornel West\n| image              = Cornel West by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| birth_name         = Cornel Ronald West\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1953|6|2}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| home_town          = [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]], U.S.\n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* Hilda Holloman ({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1977; {{abbr|div.|divorced}})<ref>{{cite book |last1=West |first1=Cornel |last2=Ritz |first2=David |author2-link=David Ritz |year=2009 |title=Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud |location=New York |publisher=SmileyBooks |pages=95, 107 |isbn=978-1-4019-2677-9}}</ref>\n* Ramona Santiago ({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1981; {{abbr|div.|divorced}}&nbsp;{{circa|1986}})<ref>{{cite book |last1=West |first1=Cornel |last2=Ritz |first2=David |author2-link=David Ritz |year=2009 |title=Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud |location=New York |publisher=SmileyBooks |pages=117\u2013119, 139 |isbn=978-1-4019-2677-9}}</ref>\n* {{marriage|Elleni Gebre Amlak|1992 }}\n {{marriage|Leslie Kotkin|2016 |2018}}\n<ref>{{cite book |last=Russell |first=Dick |year=2009 |title=Black Genius: Inspirational Portraits of African-American Leaders |edition=rev. large print |location=New York |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing |page=221 |isbn=978-1-60239-369-1}}</ref>}}\n| website            = {{official URL}}\n| education          = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Princeton University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n| thesis_title       = Ethics, Historicism and the Marxist Tradition\n| thesis_year        = 1980\n| school_tradition   = {{hlist | [[Neopragmatism]]<ref>[https://www.iep.utm.edu/pragmati/ Pragmatism \u2013 Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy]</ref> | [[existentialism]] | [[Africana philosophy]] | [[historicism]] | [[democratic socialism]] | [[radical democracy]] | [[Baptists|Baptism]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=West |first1=Cornel |last2=Ritz |first2=David |author2-link=David Ritz |year=2009 |title=Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud |location=New York |publisher=SmileyBooks |page=165 |isbn=978-1-4019-2677-9}}</ref>}}\n| influences         = {{flatlist|\n* [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]\n* [[Malcolm X]]\n* [[W.&nbsp;E.&nbsp;B. Du Bois]]\n* [[James H. Cone|James Cone]]\n* [[Karl Marx]]\n* [[Friedrich Engels]]\n* [[Richard Rorty]]\n* [[Reinhold Niebuhr]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Stone |first=Ronald H. |year=2014 |chapter=Afterword |editor-last=Weaver |editor-first=Matthew Lon |title=Applied Christian Ethics: Foundations, Economic Justice, and Politics |location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Lexington Books |page=279 |isbn=978-0-7391-9659-5}}</ref>\n* [[Sheldon Wolin]]\n* [[S\u00f8ren Kierkegaard]]\n* [[Michel Foucault]]\n* [[Paul Tillich]]\n* [[Blaise Pascal]]\n* [[Toni Morrison]]\n* [[Anton Chekhov]]\n* [[Eugene O'Neill]]\n* [[Josiah Royce]]\n* [[Simone Weil]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Schultz |first=Rick |date=June 1, 2016 |title=Challenging 'Passion' to Open Ojai Music Festival |url=https://jewishjournal.com/culture/arts_in_la/185973/ |newspaper=Jewish Journal |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Tribe Media |access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| discipline         = {{hlist | [[African-American studies]] | [[philosophy]]}}\n| workplaces         = {{unbulleted list | [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]] | [[Yale University]] | [[Harvard University]] | [[Princeton University]] | [[Dartmouth College]]}}\n| doctoral_students  = [[Leah Hunt-Hendrix]]<ref>{{cite web |date=November 22, 2016 |title=Innovator Insights: Leah Hunt-Hendrix, Founder of Solidaire Network |url=https://medium.com/invested-impact/innovator-insights-leah-hunt-hendrix-founder-of-solidaire-network-8e30f81ed48 |website=Invested Impact |access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| main_interests     = {{hlist | [[Political philosophy]] | [[philosophy of religion]] | [[ethics]] | [[race (classification of human beings)|race]] | [[democracy]] | [[liberation theology]]}}\n| notable_works      = {{unbulleted list | ''[[Race Matters]]'' (1994) | ''Democracy Matters'' (2004)}}\n}}\n'''Cornel Ronald West''' (born June 2, 1953) is numb digger, an American philosopher, political activist, social critic, author, and [[public intellectual]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/1392/cornel_west_public_intellectual|title=Cornel West: Public Intellectual|date=November 4, 2004|first=Salim|last=Muwakkil|accessdate=May 21, 2017|journal=In These Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitman.edu/newsroom/well-known-public-intellectual-cornel-west-at-whitman-december-4|title=Well-Known Public Intellectual Cornel West at Whitman December 4|date=November 19, 2003|first=Lenel|last=Parish|accessdate=May 21, 2017|publisher=[[Whitman College]]}}</ref> \nThe son of a [[Baptist]] minister, West focuses on the role of [[Race (classification of human beings)|race]], [[gender]], and [[class (social)|class]] in American society and the means by which people act and react to their \"radical conditionedness\". A [[radical democracy|radical democrat]] and [[Democratic socialism|democratic socialist]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagodsa.org/CornelWest.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-11-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217170932/http://www.chicagodsa.org/CornelWest.html |archivedate=December 17, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsausa.org/cornel_west|title=Cornel West, DSA Honorary Chair|access-date=November 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419052144/http://www.dsausa.org/cornel_west|archive-date=April 19, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> West draws intellectual contributions from multiple traditions, including [[Christianity]], the [[black church]], [[Marxism]], [[neopragmatism]], and [[transcendentalism]].<ref name=\"pragmatic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pragmatism.org/research/cont_prag_books.htm#west |title=Contemporary \u00ab Research Pragmatism Cybrary |publisher=Pragmatism.org |accessdate=2015-04-23}}</ref><ref name=\"blackbio\">\"Cornel Ronald West\". ''Contemporary Black Biography'', Volume 33. Ed. Ashyia Henderson. Gale Group, 2002. Reproduced in Biography Resource Center. Farmington Hills, Mich.: The Gale Group. 2004.</ref><ref>\"Cornel West y la pol\u00edtica de conversi\u00f3n\". Thomas Ward. ''Resistencia cultural: La naci\u00f3n en el ensayo de las Am\u00e9ricas''. Lima: Universidad Ricardo Palma, 2004, pp. 344\u2013348.</ref><ref>Nishikawa, Kinohi. \"Cornel West.\" ''The Greenwood Encyclopedia of African American Literature''. Ed. Hans Ostrom and J. David Macey, Jr. Westport, CT: Greenwood Press, 2005. 1714\u201318.</ref> Among his most influential books are ''[[Race Matters]]'' (1994) and ''Democracy Matters'' (2004).\n\nWest is an outspoken voice in [[left-wing politics in the United States]], and as such has been critical of members of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], including former President [[Barack Obama]] and [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2014/08/24/cornel_west_he_posed_as_a_progressive_and_turned_out_to_be_counterfeit_we_ended_up_with_a_wall_street_presidency_a_drone_presidency/|date=August 24, 2014|title=Cornel West: \"He posed as a progressive and turned out to be counterfeit. We ended up with a Wall Street presidency, a drone presidency\"|first=Thomas|last=Frank|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3453797/cornel-west-calls-obama-administration-a-drone-presidency/|title=Cornel West: Obama Administration is a 'Drone Presidency'|date=October 2, 2014|accessdate=May 21, 2017|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/book-party/wp/2015/01/19/has-obama-embodied-martin-luther-king-jr-s-legacy-or-betrayed-it/|title=Cornel West channels Martin Luther King Jr. to criticize Obama|first=Carlos|last=Lozada|date=January 19, 2015|accessdate=May 21, 2017|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> He has held professorships and fellowships at [[Harvard University]], [[Dartmouth College]], [[Princeton University]], [[Yale University]], [[Pepperdine University]], [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]], and the [[University of Paris]] during his career.<ref>[https://montgomery.dartmouth.edu/cornel-west Dartmouth.edu] {{webarchive |url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:tR2m5dKz7YoJ:https://montgomery.dartmouth.edu/cornel-west+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us |date=September 17, 2019 }}</ref> He is also a frequent commentator on politics and social issues in many media outlets.<ref>[http://www.cornelwest.com/about.html Cornelwest.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703022827/http://www.cornelwest.com/about.html |date=July 3, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 through 2013, West co-hosted a radio program with [[Tavis Smiley]], called ''Smiley and West''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://targetmarketnews.com/storyid10181301.htm|title=Tavis Smiley, Cornell West ending their public radio show in December|work=targetmarketnews.com|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://oppressionmonitor.us/2013/12/29/smiley-west-noam-chomsky-final-smiley-west/|title=Smiley and West \u2013 Noam Chomsky: The Final Smiley and West|work=Oppression Monitor Daily|accessdate=April 26, 2015|date=December 29, 2013}}</ref> He has also been featured in several documentaries, and made appearances in Hollywood films such as ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' and ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'', providing commentary for both films. West has also made several [[spoken word]] and [[hip hop]] albums, and due to his work, has been named [[MTV]]'s Artist of the Week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2291762/artist-of-the-week-dr-cornel-west//|title=Artist Of The Week: Dr. Cornel West by Tamar Anitai |work=MTV|accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nWest was born on June 2, 1953, in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], [[Oklahoma]],<ref name=\"influx\">{{cite web |url= http://influx.uoregon.edu/1998/west/index.html |title= Prisoner of Hope |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020209041340/http://influx.uoregon.edu/1998/west/index.html |archivedate=February 9, 2002 |accessdate=November 4, 2015 |last=Elder |first= Robert |authorlink=Robert K. Elder |year= 1998 |work=inFlux |publisher= University of Oregon School of Journalism and Communication}}</ref> and grew up in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]], where he graduated from [[John F. Kennedy High School (Sacramento, California)|John F. Kennedy High School]]. His mother, Irene (Bias), was a teacher and principal, and his father, Clifton Louis West Jr., was a [[general contractor]] for the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/topics/cornel-west |title=Cornel West Biography |publisher=Enotes.com |accessdate=2015-04-23}}</ref> Irene B. West Elementary School in [[Elk Grove, California|Elk Grove]], California, is named for his mother.<ref>{{cite journal |last=smitty |first=Fahizah |title=Opening Doors: Irene West Gave Her All as a Teacher and Principal, Now, a New School Honors Her Name and Hard Work |journal=Sacramento Bee |date=June 4, 1999 }}</ref>\n\nAs a young man, West marched in [[civil rights]] demonstrations and organized protests demanding black studies courses at his high school, where he was class president. He later wrote that, in his youth, he admired \"the sincere black militancy of [[Malcolm X]], the defiant rage of the [[Black Panther Party]], and the livid [[black theology]] of [[James H. Cone]].\"<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=Kk6ovUWs02AC&pg=PA3 |title= The Cornel West Reader |isbn= 978-0-465-09110-2 |author1= West, Cornel |date= August 13, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, after graduating from high school, he enrolled at [[Harvard College]] and took classes from the philosophers [[Robert Nozick]] and [[Stanley Cavell]]. In 1973, West graduated from Harvard ''[[Latin honors|magna cum laude]]'' in Near Eastern languages and civilization.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bc.edu/bc_org/rvp/pubaf/chronicle/v13/o21/postings.html |title=Author Cornel West to Speak in Robsham Theater Oct. 30 |date=October 21, 2004 |publisher=The [[Boston College]] Chronicle |accessdate=January 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602022035/http://www.bc.edu/bc_org/rvp/pubaf/chronicle/v13/o21/postings.html |archive-date=June 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He credits Harvard with exposing him to a broader range of ideas, influenced by his professors as well as the Black Panther Party. West says his Christianity prevented him from joining the BPP, instead choosing to work in local breakfast, prison, and church programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.democracynow.org/2009/9/30/dr_cornel_west_on_his_new |title=Dr. Cornel West Releases Long-Awaited Memoir, \"Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud\" |author=Goodman, Amy |date=September 30, 2009 |work=Democracy Now |accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref> After completing his undergraduate work at Harvard, West enrolled at [[Princeton University]] where he received a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (PhD) degree in 1980, becoming the first African American to graduate from Princeton with a PhD degree in philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/faultlines/2010/03/201031162433794100.html |title=Cornel West |publisher=Aljazeera.com |date=2010-03-11 |accessdate=2015-04-23}}</ref> At Princeton, West was heavily influenced by [[Richard Rorty]]'s [[neopragmatism]].<ref name=Mendieta/> Rorty remained a close friend and colleague of West's for many years following West's graduation. The title of West's [[dissertation]] was ''Ethics, Historicism and the Marxist Tradition'',<ref>{{cite document |title= ''Ethics, historicism and the Marxist tradition'' |id = {{ProQuest|303076528}}}}</ref> which was later revised and published under the title ''The Ethical Dimensions of Marxist Thought''.<ref name=Mendieta>{{cite book |last=Mendieta |first=Eduardo |title=Global Fragments: Globalizations, Latinamericanisms, and Critical Theory |year=2007 |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany, New York |isbn=978-0-7914-7257-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CycoIHOtyhYC&pg=PA173 |page=173 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Academic appointments ===\n\nIn his late-20s, he returned to Harvard as a [[W.&nbsp;E.&nbsp;B. Du Bois]] [[Fellow]] before becoming an assistant professor at [[Union Theological Seminary in the City of New York]]. In 1984, he went to [[Yale Divinity School]] in what eventually became a joint appointment in [[American studies]]. While at Yale, he participated in campus protests for a clerical labor union and [[divestment]] from [[apartheid]] South Africa. One of the protests resulted in his being arrested and jailed. As punishment, the university administration canceled his leave for the spring term in 1987, leading him to commute from Yale in [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], [[Connecticut]], where he was teaching two classes, across the Atlantic Ocean to the [[University of Paris]].<ref name=\"blackbio\"/>\n\nHe then returned to Union Theological Seminary <!-- restore when you can find a source: and taught at [[Haverford College]] in Pennsylvania --> for one year before going to Princeton to become a professor of religion and director of the Program in [[African American studies|African-American Studies]] from 1988 to 1994.<ref name=blackbio/> After Princeton, he accepted an appointment as professor of African-American studies at Harvard University, with a joint appointment at the [[Harvard Divinity School]].<ref name=Aaseng>{{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Aaseng |editor-first=Nathan |encyclopedia=African-American Religious Leaders |title=Cornel West |year=2003 |publisher=Facts on File |location=New York |isbn=0-8160-4878-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/africanamericanr00aase_0/page/237 237] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/africanamericanr00aase_0/page/237 }} {{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref> West taught one of the university's most popular courses, an introductory class on African-American studies.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-08-16/features/0208160010_1_cornel-west-president-of-harvard-university-prostate-surgery |title=Cornel West's difficult road to Princeton |last=Duke |first=Lynn |date=August 16, 2002 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=October 22, 2011 }}</ref> In 1998, he was appointed the first [[Alphonse Fletcher]] [[Endowed professor|University Professor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aaas.fas.harvard.edu/about/moments |title=Other Key Moments in the Department |publisher=Department of African and African American Studies, Harvard University |accessdate=October 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006185200/http://aaas.fas.harvard.edu/about/moments |archivedate=October 6, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> West utilized this new position to teach in not only African-American studies, but also in divinity, religion, and philosophy.<ref name=Aaseng/> West left Harvard after a widely publicized<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/16/us/defector-indignant-at-president-of-harvard.html|title=Defector Indignant at President of Harvard|first=Pam Belluck With Jacques|last=Steinberg|date=April 16, 2002|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> dispute with then-President [[Lawrence Summers]] in 2002.<ref>Cornel West. Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud. A Memoir. Hay House, Inc. {{ISBN|978-1401921903}}. 1985, pp. 216\u2013230</ref> That year, West returned to Princeton, where he helped create \"one of the world\u2019s leading centers for African-American studies\" according to [[Shirley Tilghman]], Princeton's president in 2011.<ref name=NYT2011>{{cite news|last1=Goodstein|first1=Laurie|title=Cornel West to Take a Job in New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/17/nyregion/cornel-west-returning-to-union-theological-seminary.html?_r=0|accessdate=26 August 2014|work=New York Times|date=November 16, 2011}}</ref>  In 2012, West left Princeton and returned to the institution where he began his teaching career, Union Theological Seminary.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/17/nyregion/cornel-west-returning-to-union-theological-seminary.html | work=The New York Times | first=Laurie | last=Goodstein | title=Cornel West Returning to Union Theological Seminary | date=November 16, 2011}}</ref> His departure from Princeton, unlike his departure from Harvard, was quite amicable. As of 2017, he continues to teach occasional courses at Princeton in an [[emeritus]] capacity as the Class of 1943 University Professor in the Center for African American Studies.<ref name=NYT2011 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://religion.princeton.edu/people/faculty/emeriti-faculty/cornel-west/|title=Cornel West \u2013 Department of Religion|author=|date=August 25, 2016|website=princeton.edu|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe recipient of more than 20 honorary degrees and an [[American Book Award]],<ref name=\"pragmatic\"/> he has written or contributed to over twenty published books. West is a long-time member of the [[Democratic Socialists of America]], for which he now serves as an honorary chair.<ref name=blackbio/> He is also a co-founder of the [[Network of Spiritual Progressives]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spiritualprogressives.org/newsite/?page_id=33 |title=NSP Co-Founders |publisher=Network of Spiritual Progressives |accessdate=October 22, 2011 }}</ref> West is on the advisory board of the [[International Bridges to Justice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibj.org/about-us/directors-and-advisors/ |title=Board of Directors and Advisors |publisher=International Bridges to Justice |accessdate=October 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126142945/http://www.ibj.org/about-us/directors-and-advisors/ |archivedate=November 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he received a special recognition from the [[World Cultural Council]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Special Recognitions 2008 |publisher=[[World Cultural Council]] |url=http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/memories-ceremony2008-SpecialRecognitions.php |accessdate=August 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105183105/http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/memories-ceremony2008-SpecialRecognitions.php |archivedate=November 5, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nWest is also a member of [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] fraternity and its [[World Policy Council]], a [[think tank]] whose purpose is to expand Alpha Phi Alpha's involvement in politics and social and current policy to encompass international concerns.<ref name=\"WPC#5\">{{cite journal|first=Horace |last=Dawson |authorlink=Horace Dawson |author2=[[Edward Brooke]], [[Henry Ponder]], Vinton R. Anderson, [[Bobby William Austin]], [[Ron Dellums]], [[Kenton Keith (diplomat)|Kenton Keith]], Huel D. Perkins, [[Charles B. Rangel|Charles Rangel]], Clathan McClain Ross, and Cornel West |title=The Centenary Report of the Alpha Phi Alpha World Policy Council |publisher=Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity |date=July 2006 |url=http://www.alpha-phi-alpha.com/Resources/ImageFile/File/image/WPC06-WEB.pdf |accessdate=May 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225132901/http://www.alpha-phi-alpha.com/Resources/ImageFile/File/image/WPC06-WEB.pdf |archivedate=February 25, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nWest has been widely cited in the popular press.<ref>{{cite document |title=Cornel West Quitting Harvard |last1=Fletcher |first1=Michael A. |last2=Ferdinand |first2=Pamela |date=April 13, 2002 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|409336618}}}}</ref> His scholarship has been criticized as well as praised; ''[[The New Republic]]'' literary editor [[Leon Wieseltier]] called West's writing \"sectarian, humorless, pedantic and self-endeared\".<ref>Wieseltier, quoted in {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Wood |first1=Mark David |title=Cornel West and the Politics of Prophetic Pragmatism |date=2000 |publisher=University of Illinois Press |isbn=0-25-202578-4 |page=4 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Cornel_West_and_the_Politics_of_Propheti.html?id=RVdQ0mhiapUC&q=wieseltier}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Harvard announced that West would be leaving Union Theological Seminary to hold a joint nontenured appointment at the [[Harvard Divinity School]] and the Harvard Department of African and African-American Studies as Professor of the Practice of Public Philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aaas.fas.harvard.edu/people/cornel-r-west|title=Cornel R. West|author=|date=|website=aaas.fas.harvard.edu|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hds.harvard.edu/people/cornel-r-west|title=Cornel R. West|author=|date=|website=hds.harvard.edu|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/20/us/cornel-west-harvard.html|title=Cornel West Will Return to Teach at Harvard|last=Seelye|first=Katharine Q.|date=2016-11-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-03-25|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Entertainment career===\nWest appears as Councillor West in both ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' and ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'' and also provides the voice for this character in the video game ''[[Enter the Matrix]]''.<ref name=agger>Agger, Michael. [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/18/movies/film-and-the-oscar-for-best-scholar.html FILM; And the Oscar for Best Scholar . . .]. ''The New York Times''. May 18, 2003. Retrieved March 7, 2011.</ref> In addition, West provides philosophical commentary on all three Matrix films in [[The Ultimate Matrix Collection]], along with the [[Integral theory (Ken Wilber)|integral theorist]] [[Ken Wilber]].<ref>Pratt, Doug. [http://www.allbusiness.com/services/motion-pictures/4819022-1.html The Ultimate Matrix Collection]. ''The Hollywood Reporter'' via AllBusiness. December 6, 2004. Retrieved March 7, 2011. {{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe has made several appearances in documentary films also, such as the 2008 film ''[[Examined Life]]'', a documentary featuring several academics discussing philosophy in real-world contexts. West, \"driving through Manhattan,&nbsp;... compares philosophy to jazz and blues, reminding us how intense and invigorating a life of the mind can be.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Examined Life (2008) \u2013 Plot Summary |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1279083/plotsummary}}</ref> He also appears in conversation with [[Bill Withers]] in the Bill Withers documentary, ''[[Still Bill (film)|Still Bill]]''.\n\nWest has made frequent appearances on the political talk show ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Real Time with Bill Maher: Full Cast and Crew |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0350448/fullcredits#cast |accessdate=April 21, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA character based on West and events in his career appeared in the ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' episode \"[[Anti-Thesis]]\", significant for introducing the recurring villain character Nicole Wallace.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://gseis.ucla.edu/faculty/kellner/essays/academicscoundrls.pdf \n |title=Academic Scandals and the Broadcast Media \n |author1=Rhonda Hammer \n |author2=Douglas Kellner \n |publisher=Gseis.ucla.edu \n |accessdate=2015-04-23 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626082720/http://www.gseis.ucla.edu/faculty/kellner/essays/academicscoundrls.pdf \n |archivedate=June 26, 2010 \n |df=mdy \n}} \n</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, West guest-starred in the sixth season of the American television comedy series ''[[30 Rock]]'', \"[[What Will Happen to the Gang Next Year?]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/30-rock-what-will-happen-to-the-gang-next-year-73998|title=30 Rock: \"What Will Happen To The Gang Next Year?\"|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|first=Meredith|last=Blake|date=May 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn the musical front, West recorded a recitation of [[John Mellencamp]]'s song \"Jim Crow\" for inclusion on the singer's [[box set]] ''[[On the Rural Route 7609]]'' in 2009.<ref name=princetonian/>\n\nIn 2010, he completed recording with the Cornel West Theory, a [[hip hop]] band endorsed by West.<ref name=princetonian>Han, Lisa. [http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/2010/02/04/24984/ Cornel West Theory] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414134335/http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/2010/02/04/24984/ |date=April 14, 2010 }}. ''Daily Princetonian''. February 4, 2010. Retrieved March 7, 2011.</ref> He has also released several hip-hop/soul/spoken word albums. In 2001, West released his first album, ''Sketches of My Culture''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/aponline/20011106/aponline142029_000.htm|title=Harvard Professor Makes Hip-Hop CD|work=[[Washington Post]]|first=Audie N.|last=Cornish|date=November 6, 2001|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> ''Street Knowledge'' followed in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/cornel-west/Content?oid=1073599|title=Cornel West \u2013 Street Knowledge|work=[[East Bay Express]]|first=Rachel|last=Swan|date=April 21, 2004|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> In 2007, West released ''Never Forget: A Journey of Revelations'', his third album which included collaborations with the likes of [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Jill Scott]], [[Andre 3000]], [[KRS-One]], and the late [[Gerald Levert]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2007/09/06/62046-cd-review-cornel-west/|title=CD Review: Cornel West|work=[[Tucson Citizen]]|first=Brett|last=Johnson|date=September 6, 2007|accessdate=October 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011022753/http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2007/09/06/62046-cd-review-cornel-west/|archive-date=October 11, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> West appeared on [[Immortal Technique]]'s song \"Sign of the Times\", which appeared on the 2011 album ''[[The Martyr (album)|The Martyr]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.citypages.com/gimmenoise/2011/10/immortal_technique.php |title=Immortal Technique talks about his new free album The Martyr and Occupy MN |work=[[City Pages]] |first=Rebecca |last=McDonald |date=October 27, 2011 |accessdate=October 21, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529211214/http://blogs.citypages.com/gimmenoise/2011/10/immortal_technique.php |archivedate=May 29, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> In 2012, he was featured on [[Brother Ali]]'s song \"Letter to My Countrymen\", which appeared on the album ''[[Mourning in America and Dreaming in Color]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16941-brother-ali-mourning-in-america-and-dreaming-in-color/|title=Brother Ali: Mourning In America and Dreaming In Color|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|first=Nate|last=Patrin|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, [[Robert P. George]] and West participated in an \"assembly series\" discussion at [[Washington University in St. Louis]] titled \"Liberal Arts Education: What\u2019s The Point?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://humanities.wustl.edu/events/liberal-arts-education-what%E2%80%99s-point-cornel-west-robert-george-conversation|title=Liberal Arts Education: What's The Point? Cornel West & Robert George in Conversation|date=2019-03-07|website=Center for the Humanities|language=en|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\nHis voice can be downloaded for directional guidance purposes as a downloadable option on some personal GPS-navigation device models by company [[TomTom]].\n\n==Dispute with Lawrence Summers==\nIn 2000, the economist and former US Treasury Secretary [[Lawrence Summers]] became president of Harvard. Soon after, Summers held a private meeting with West, where he reportedly rebuked West for missing too many classes, contributing to [[grade inflation]], neglecting serious scholarship, and spending too much time on his economically profitable projects.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Who is Cornel West? |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/fyi/teachers.ednews/01/10/west.harvard.ap/ |publisher=[[CNN|Cable News Network]] |date= January 10, 2002 |accessdate=January 21, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226113730/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/fyi/teachers.ednews/01/10/west.harvard.ap/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=December 26, 2007}}</ref> Summers reportedly suggested that West produce an academic book befitting his professorial position, as his recent output had consisted primarily of co-written and edited volumes. According to some reports, Summers also objected to West's production of a CD, the critically panned ''Sketches of My Culture'', and to his political campaigning, including an alleged three weeks to promote [[Bill Bradley]]'s [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2000|presidential]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jacques |last=Steinberg |authorlink=Jacques Steinberg |title=At Odds With Harvard President, Black-Studies Stars Eye Princeton |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F06E4D71F31F93AA15751C1A9679C8B63 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |location=New York City |date=November 29, 2001 |accessdate=January 21, 2008}}</ref> West contended he had missed only one class during his tenure at Harvard \"in order to give a keynote address at a Harvard-sponsored conference on AIDS.\" Summers also allegedly suggested that since West held the rank of [[Harvard University Professor]] and thus reported directly to the President, he should meet with Summers regularly to discuss the progress of his academic production.<ref name=\"indignant\">{{cite news |first=Pam |last=Belluck |author2=Jacques Steinberg |title=Defector Indignant at President of Harvard |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0DE6DB113CF935A25757C0A9649C8B63 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |location=New York City |date=April 16, 2002 |accessdate=January 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nSummers refused to comment on the details of his conversation with West, except to express hope that West would remain at Harvard. Soon after, West was hospitalized for [[prostate cancer]]. West noted that Summers failed to send him get-well wishes until weeks after his surgery, whereas newly installed Princeton president [[Shirley Tilghman]] had contacted him frequently before and after his treatment.<ref name=\"indignant\" />\n\nIn 2002 West left Harvard University to return to Princeton. West lashed out at Summers in public interviews, calling him \"the [[Ariel Sharon]] of higher education\" on NPR's ''[[The Tavis Smiley Show|Tavis Smiley Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/020415.cwest.html |title=Cornel West Outlines \"Pull toward Princeton\" and \"Push from Harvard\" in Exclusive Interview with NPR's Tavis Smiley |publisher=Npr.org |date=January 7, 2002 |accessdate=March 7, 2011}}</ref> In response to these remarks, five Princeton faculty members, led by professor of molecular biology Jacques Robert Fresco, said they looked with \"strong disfavor upon his characterization\" of Summers and that \"such an analogy carries innuendoes and implications&nbsp;... that many on the Princeton faculty find highly inappropriate, indeed repugnant and intolerable.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Cornel West's Analogy |author=Jacques R. Fresco |newspaper=The New York Times |date=April 24, 2002 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/24/opinion/l-cornel-west-s-analogy-697680.html?pagewanted=1 |url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n[[Harvard University]]'s undergraduate student newspaper, ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'', suggested in October 2002 that the premise of the ''[[Law and Order: Criminal Intent]]'' episode \"[[Anti-Thesis]]\" was based on West's conflicts with Summers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell |first=Andrew C. |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/printerfriendly.aspx?ref=254638 |title=Ripped from Harvard Headlines &#124; News &#124; The Harvard Crimson |publisher=Thecrimson.com |date=October 16, 2002 |accessdate=March 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013164830/http://www.thecrimson.com/printerfriendly.aspx?ref=254638 |archivedate=October 13, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n\n===Views on race in the United States===\nWest has called the US a \"racist patriarchal\" nation where [[white supremacy]] continues to define everyday life. \"White America\", he writes, \"has been historically weak-willed in ensuring racial justice and has continued to resist fully accepting the humanity of blacks.\" This has resulted, he says, in the creation of many \"degraded and oppressed people hungry for identity, meaning, and self-worth.\" West attributes most of the black community's problems to \"existential angst derive[d] from the lived experience of ontological wounds and emotional scars inflicted by white supremacist beliefs and images permeating U.S. society and culture.\"<ref>Cornel West, ''Race Matters'', p. 27, 2001 edition, {{ISBN|978-0-8070-0972-7}}</ref>\n\nIn West's view, the [[September 11 attacks]] gave white Americans a glimpse of what it means to be a black person in the United States\u2014feeling \"unsafe, unprotected, subject to random violence, and hatred\" for who they are.<ref name=\"democracy matters\">Cornel West, ''Democracy Matters,'' p. 20, 2004, {{ISBN|0-14-303583-5}}</ref> \"The ugly terrorist attacks on innocent civilians on 9/11\", he said, \"plunged the whole country into the blues.\"<ref name=\"democracy matters\"/>\n\nWest was arrested on October 13, 2014, while protesting against the [[shooting of Michael Brown]] and participating in [[Ferguson October]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornel West arrested; video of #FergusonOctober from Fusion's Tim Pool|url=http://fusion.net/video/21051/unrest-in-st-louis/|website=Fusion.net|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cornel West in Ferguson: 'I Came Here to Go to Jail'|url=http://www.truthdig.com/avbooth/item/cornel_west_in_ferguson_i_came_here_to_go_to_jail_20141013|website=Truth Dig|publisher=Truth Dig|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> and again on August 10, 2015, while demonstrating outside a courthouse in [[St. Louis]] on the one-year anniversary of Brown's death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/cornel-west-dozens-arrested-missouri-protests-article-1.2320829 |title=Cornel West among dozens of protesters arrested at St. Louis courthouse as state of emergency declared in Missouri |first1=Cameron |last1=Joseph |first2=Corky |last2=Siemaszko |date=August 10, 2015 |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |accessdate=August 11, 2015 }}</ref> The 2015 documentary film ''[[Bars4justice|#Bars4Justice]]'' includes footage of West demonstrating and being arrested in Ferguson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nation19.com/nation19s-new-short-film-filmed-in-ferguson-set-to-premier-in-phoenix/ |title=Filmmakers bring Ferguson to Phoenix's Hip Hop community\u2026 Sheriff Arpaio not invited |date=September 30, 2015 |work=[[Nation19]] |accessdate=April 23, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\n[[File:Cornel West & Robert P. George (28154741749).jpg|right|thumb|West (left) with [[Robert P. George]] (right) in 2018]]\nWest has described himself as a \"non-[[Marxist]] socialist\" (partly because he does not view Marxism and Christianity as reconcilable)<ref>{{cite book |last=West |first=Cornel |title=The Cornel West Reader |year=1999 |publisher=Basic Civitas Books |location=New York |isbn=0-465-09109-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bNJD8g1e-QQC&pg=PA13 |page=13 }}</ref> and serves as honorary chair of the [[Democratic Socialists of America]], which he has described as \"the first multiracial, socialist organization close enough to my politics that I could join\".<ref name=blackbio/> He also described himself as a \"radical democrat, suspicious of all forms of authority\" in the ''Matrix''-themed documentary ''The Burly Man Chronicles''.<ref>{{cite video |people=Cornel West |title=[[The Ultimate Matrix Collection]] }}</ref>\n\nWest believes that \"the overthrow of [[Saddam Hussein]]'s ugly totalitarian regime was desirable,\"<ref>Cornel West, ''Democracy Matters,'' p. 58, 2004, {{ISBN|0-14-303583-5}}</ref> but that the [[war in Iraq]] was the result of \"dishonest manipulation\" on the part of the Bush administration.<ref>Cornel West, ''Democracy Matters,'' p. 101, 2004, {{ISBN|0-14-303583-5}}</ref> He asserts that Bush administration [[war hawk|hawks]] \"are not simply conservative elites and right-wing ideologues\", but rather are \"evangelical nihilists&nbsp;\u2013 drunk with power and driven by grand delusions of American domination of the world\". He adds, \"We are [now] experiencing the sad gangsterization of America, an unbridled grasp at power, wealth, and status.\" Viewing capitalism as the root cause of these alleged American lusts, West warns, \"[[market fundamentalism|Free-market fundamentalism]] trivializes the concern for public interest. It puts fear and insecurity in the hearts of anxiety-ridden workers. It also makes money-driven, poll-obsessed elected officials deferential to corporate goals of profit \u2013 often at the cost of the common good.\"<ref>[http://www.theglobalist.com/StoryId.aspx?StoryId=4262 Theglobalist.com]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203073821/http://www.theglobalist.com/StoryId.aspx?StoryId=4262 |date=December 3, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nWest has been involved with such projects as the [[Million Man March]] and [[Russell Simmons]]'s Hip-Hop Summit, and worked with such public figures as [[Louis Farrakhan]]<ref name=\"influx\"/> and [[Al Sharpton]], whose 2004 presidential campaign West advised.<ref>{{cite document |title=Cornel West, Cloaked in Street Smarts |last=Givhan |first=Robin |authorlink=Robin Givhan |date=January 25, 2002 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|409271497}}}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, West worked as a senior advisor to [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] [[President of the United States|presidential]] candidate [[Bill Bradley]]. When Bradley lost in the primaries, West became a prominent endorser of [[Ralph Nader]], even speaking at some Nader rallies. Some [[United States Green Party|Greens]] sought to draft West to run as a presidential candidate in 2004. West declined, citing his active participation in the [[Al Sharpton]] campaign. West, along with other prominent Nader 2000 supporters, signed the \"Vote to Stop Bush\" statement urging progressive voters in swing states to vote for [[John Kerry]], despite strong disagreements with many of Kerry's policies.<ref>\"Senators Hillary Clinton and John Kerry are exemplary paternalistic nihilists... Their centrist or conservative policies... are opportunistic efforts to satisfy centrist or conservative constituencies.\" Cornel West, ''Democracy Matters,'' p. 35-36, 2004, {{ISBN|0-14-303583-5}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2002 West and Rabbi [[Michael Lerner (rabbi)|Michael Lerner]] performed civil disobedience by sitting in the street in front of the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] \"in solidarity with suffering Palestinian and Israeli brothers and sisters.\" West said, \"We must keep in touch with the humanity of both sides.\"<ref>{{cite document |title=Peace Demonstrators Arrested, Without Much Conviction |last=Montgomery |first=David |date=April 12, 2002 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|409255662}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://supportcom.com/PEP/www.pepeace.org/current_reprints/10/Thoughts_On_Antisemitism.htm |title=Thoughts on Anti-Semitism |publisher=Supportcom.com |date=December 6, 2005 |accessdate=March 7, 2011}}</ref> In May 2007 West joined a demonstration against \"injustices faced by the Palestinian people resulting from the Israeli occupation\" and \"to bring attention to this 40-year travesty of justice\". In 2011, West called on the [[University of Arizona]] to divest from companies profiting from the [[Israeli occupation of the Palestinian territories]].<ref>[http://nomoredeaths.org/University-of-Arizona-NMD/cornel-west-ua-letter.html Nomordeaths.org] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719162402/http://nomoredeaths.org/University-of-Arizona-NMD/cornel-west-ua-letter.html |date=July 19, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWest also serves as co-chair of the [[Tikkun Community]]. He co-chaired the National Parenting Organization's Task Force on Parent Empowerment and participated in President [[Bill Clinton]]'s National Conversation on Race. He has publicly endorsed ''[[In These Times]]'' magazine by calling it: \"The most creative and challenging news magazine of the American left\". He is also a contributing editor for ''[[Sojourners]]'' magazine.\n\nWest supports [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) in its Kentucky Fried Cruelty campaign, aimed at eliminating what PETA describes as [[KFC]]'s inhumane treatment of chickens. West is quoted on PETA flyers: \"Although most people don't know chickens as well as they know cats and dogs, chickens are interesting individuals with personalities and interests every bit as developed as the dogs and cats with whom many of us share our lives.\"\n\nIn 2008, West contributed his insights on the current global issue of modernized slavery and [[human trafficking]] in the documentary ''Call+Response''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.callandresponse.com |title=Call + Response |publisher=Callandresponse.com |accessdate=March 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223190730/http://www.callandresponse.com/ |archive-date=February 23, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> West is a member of the [[Campaign for Peace and Democracy]].\n\nIn 2011, West addressed his frustration about some critics of the [[Occupy Wall Street]], who remark about the movement's lack of a clear and unified message. West replied by saying:\n<blockquote>\nIt's impossible to translate the issue of the greed of Wall Street into one demand, or two demands. We're talking about a democratic awakening...you're talking about raising political consciousness so it spills over all parts of the country, so people can begin to see what's going on through a set of different lens, and then you begin to highlight what the more detailed demands would be. Because in the end we're really talking about what [[Martin Luther King Jr.|Martin King]] would call a revolution: A transfer of power from [[Business oligarch|oligarch]]s to everyday people of all colors. And that is a step by step process.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornel West on Occupy Wall Street: It's the Makings of a U.S. Autumn Responding to the Arab Spring|url=http://www.democracynow.org/blog/2011/9/29/cornel_west_on_occupy_wall_street_its_the_makings_of_a_us_autumn_responding_to_the_arab_spring|publisher=[[Democracy Now]]|date=September 29, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> \n</blockquote>\n\nOn October 16, 2011, West was in [[Washington, DC]], participating in the [[Occupy D.C.]] protests on the steps of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] over the court's decision in the ''[[Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission]]'' case the previous year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/guest-voices/post/dr-cornel-west-honors-dr-martin-luther-king-jr-by-going-to-jail/2011/10/17/gIQA9oLRrL_blog.html |title=Dr. Cornel West honors Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. by going to jail |author=Thisltethwaite, Susan Brooks |date=October 17, 2011 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref> Five days later, he was arrested during an Occupy Wall Street protest in [[Harlem]] against the New York Police Department's [[stop and frisk]] policy.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/10/22/cornel-west-arrested-again-at-occupy-protest/ |title=Cornel West Arrested Again at Occupy Protest |author=Carbone, Nick |date=October 22, 2011 |journal=Time |accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, West co-initiated the Stop Mass Incarceration Network, a project of the [[Revolutionary Communist Party USA]]. Later that year, he and RCP chairman [[Bob Avakian]] took part in a filmed discussion on \"Religion and Revolution\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://revcom.us/film|title=Revolution and Religion: The Fight for Emancipation and the Role of Religion|website=Revcom.us|accessdate=December 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, West was one of a group of interfaith, multiracial clergy who took part in a counter-protest at the [[Unite the Right Rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]], [[Virginia]]; West averred that [[Antifa (U.S.)|Antifa]] had saved their lives.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.democracynow.org/2017/8/14/cornel_west_rev_toni_blackmon_clergy |title=Cornel West & Rev. Traci Blackmon: Clergy in Charlottesville Were Trapped by Torch-Wielding Nazis |date=August 14, 2017 |website=Democracy Now! |access-date=August 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Views on Barack Obama===\nWest has often spoken about the lack of adequate black leadership and how it leads to doubt within black communities as to their political potential to ensure change.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Black Popular Culture|last=Wallace|first=Michele|publisher=Bay Press|year=1992|isbn=978-1-56584-459-9|location=Seattle|pages=45}}</ref> Cornel West publicly supported [[Democratic Party presidential candidates, 2008|2008 Democratic presidential candidate]] Senator [[Barack Obama]]. He spoke to over 1,000 of his supporters at the [[Apollo Theater]] in [[Harlem]], on November 29, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stacy|last=Parker Aab|title=Obama, Race, and the Right Side of History|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/stacy-parker-aab/obama-race-and-the-righ_b_74871.html|work=The Huffington News|publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc.|date=October 30, 2007|accessdate=January 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWest criticized President Barack Obama when he won the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] in 2009, saying that it would be difficult for Obama to be \"a war president with a peace prize\". West further retracted his support for Obama in an April 2011 interview, stating that Obama is \"a black mascot of Wall Street oligarchs and a black muppet of corporate plutocrats. And now he has become head of the American killing machine and is proud of it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/10/10/cornel-west-comments-on-o_n_316476.html|title=Cornel West Comments on Obama's Nobel Peace Prize: Hard to Be War President with Peace Prize|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=October 10, 2009|accessdate=October 28, 2009 }}</ref><ref>Schneider, Matt. [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/wild-shoutfest-between-al-sharpton-and-cornel-west-on-obamas-leadership-on-racial-issues/ \"Wild Shoutfest Between Al Sharpton And Cornel West On Obama And Race\"]. mediaite.com. April 11, 2011. Retrieved 2011-4-11.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/the_obama_deception_why_cornel_west_went_ballistic_20110516 |title=Chris Hedges: The Obama Deception: Why Cornel West Went Ballistic \u2013 Chris Hedges |publisher=Truthdig.com |accessdate=2015-04-23}}</ref> In November 2012, West said in an interview that he considered Obama a \"[[Rockefeller Republican]] in [[blackface]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/cornel-west-obama-a-republican-in-blackface-black-msnbc-hosts-are-selling-their-souls/|title=Cornel West: Obama A 'Republican In Blackface,' Black MSNBC Hosts Are 'Selling Their Souls'|last=Kirell|first=Andrew|date=November 12, 2012|work=[[Mediaite]]|accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2012/11/30/an-interview-with-cornel-west-on-occupy-obama-and-marx/|title=An Interview with Cornel West on Occupy, Obama and Marx|work=[[CounterPunch]]|date=November 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, West participated in a \"Poverty Tour\" with [[Tavis Smiley]], his co-host on the [[Public Radio International]] program ''Smiley & West''. The tour became a two-part special on their radio program as well as a five-night special on the PBS television program ''Tavis Smiley''. They recounted their experience on the tour in their 2012 bestselling book ''The Rich and the Rest of Us''. The stated aim of the tour was to highlight the plight of the [[poverty in the United States|impoverished population of the United States]] prior to the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 presidential election]], whose candidates West and Smiley stated had ignored the plight of the poor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2011/8/9/cornel_west_tavis_smiley_on_obama|title=Cornel West & Tavis Smiley on Obama: 'Many of Us Are Exploring Other Possibilities in Coming Election'|publisher=Democracy Now!|date=August 9, 2011|accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref>[[File:Cornel West Introduces Bernie Sanders in South Carolina.webm|thumb|West introduces [[Bernie Sanders]] at a September 2015 [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|campaign]] rally in South Carolina]]In 2013, West referred to Obama's speech at the 50th anniversary celebration of [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]'s \"[[I Have a Dream]]\" speech as contradictory and as \"pretty words that hide ugly deeds.\" West then goes on to state, \"Martin Luther King Jr. had a dream. Barack Obama's got drones. Martin Luther King Jr. had prophetic missions. Barack Obama's got deadly missiles that he\u2019s ready to use.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/melanie-hunter/cornel-west-mlk-had-dream-barack-obama-s-got-drones|title=Cornel West: MLK Had a Dream; 'Barack Obama's Got Drones'|author=|date=September 5, 2013|website=CNS News|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, West gave an interview slamming Obama, calling him a \"counterfeit\" who posed as a progressive. West defined Obama's presidency as \"a Wall Street presidency, a drone presidency, a national security presidency.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|title=Cornel West: \"He posed as a progressive and turned out to be counterfeit. We ended up with a Wall Street presidency, a drone presidency\"|date=August 24, 2014|author= Thomas Frank |url= http://www.salon.com/2014/08/24/cornel_west_he_posed_as_a_progressive_and_turned_out_to_be_counterfeit_we_ended_up_with_a_wall_street_presidency_a_drone_presidency/|accessdate=2014-08-31}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 presidential election ===\nIn 2015, West expressed his support for Democratic contender [[Bernie Sanders]] during an interview on ''CNN Tonight''. West argued that Sanders' plans to divert wealth from Wall Street elites to the poorest members of society would be beneficial for the African-American community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ringoffireradio.com/2015/08/civil-rights-activist-cornel-west-throws-support-behind-bernie-sanders/|title=Civil Rights Activist Cornel West Throws Support Behind Bernie Sanders|publisher=Ring of Fire|date=August 19, 2015|accessdate=August 19, 2015}}</ref> On August 24, 2015, West tweeted, \"I endorse Brother @BernieSanders because he is a long-distance runner with integrity in the struggle for justice for over 50 years.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/08/25/bernie-sanders-gets-stamp-of-approval-from-cornel-west/?_r=0 Bernie Sanders Gets Stamp of Approval From Cornel West]. ''The New York Times.'' August 25, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, after Sanders exited the presidential race, West endorsed [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] nominee [[Jill Stein]] and her running mate [[Ajamu Baraka]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/287829-sanders-ally-cornel-west-backs-green-candidate |title=Sanders ally Cornel West backs Green candidate |first=Mark |last=Hensch |date=July 14, 2016 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=July 15, 2016 }}</ref> West, who is critical of the current US [[interventionism (politics)|interventionist]] foreign policy, referred to Democratic nominee [[Hillary Clinton]] as a \"[[neoliberal]] disaster\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2016/7/18/why_a_member_of_the_democratic|title=Cornel West: Why I Endorse Green Party's Jill Stein Over \"Neoliberal Disaster\" Hillary Clinton|author=|date=|website=democracynow.org|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref> and accused Clinton of merely posing as a [[progressivism in the United States|progressive]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2016/3/9/bernie_or_hillary_cornel_west_dolores|title=Bernie or Hillary? Cornel West & Dolores Huerta Debate After Sanders' Upset Win in Michigan|author=|date=|website=democracynow.org|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the victory of [[Donald Trump]], West contended in an op-ed for ''[[The Guardian]]'' that white working- and middle-class voters \"rejected the economic neglect of [[neoliberal]] policies and the self-righteous arrogance of elites\", yet \"supported a candidate who appeared to blame their social misery on minorities, and who alienated Mexican immigrants, Muslims, black people, Jews, gay people, women and China in the process.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/nov/17/american-neoliberalism-cornel-west-2016-election Goodbye, American neoliberalism. A new era is here]. ''The Guardian.'' 17 November 2016.</ref>\n\n=== 2020 presidential election ===\nWest once again put his support behind [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders 2020 presidential campaign|2020 campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2019/03/07/cornel-west-on-bernie-trump-and-racism/|title=Deconstructed Podcast: Cornel West on Bernie, Trump, and Racism|last=Deconstructed|date=2019-03-07|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\n== Published works ==\n* \"Black Theology and Marxist Thought\" (1979) \u2013 essay\n* ''Prophesy Deliverance! An Afro-American Revolutionary Christianity'' (1982)\n* ''Post-Analytic Philosophy'', edited with John Rajchman (1985)\n* ''Prophetic Fragments'' (1988)\n* ''The American Evasion of Philosophy: A Genealogy of Pragmatism'' (1989)\n* ''Breaking Bread: Insurgent Black Intellectual Life'' (with [[bell hooks]], 1991)\n* ''The Ethical Dimensions of Marxist Thought'' (1991)\n* ''Prophetic Thought in Postmodern Times: Beyond Eurocentrism and Multiculturalism'' (1993)\n* ''[[Race Matters]]'' (1993)\n* ''Keeping Faith: Philosophy and Race in America'' (1994)\n* ''Jews and Blacks: A Dialogue on Race, Religion, and Culture in America'' (with [[rabbi]] [[Michael Lerner (rabbi)|Michael Lerner]], 1995)\n* ''[[The Future of the Race]]'' (with [[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]], 1996)\n* ''Restoring Hope: Conversations on the Future of Black America'' (1997)\n* ''The War Against Parents: What We Can Do for America's Beleaguered Moms and Dads'' (with [[Sylvia Ann Hewlett]], 1998)\n* ''The Future of American Progressivism'' (with [[Roberto Unger]], 1998)\n* ''The African-American Century: How Black Americans Have Shaped Our Century'' (with [[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]], 2000)\n* ''Democracy Matters: Winning the Fight Against Imperialism'' (2004)\n* Commentary on ''[[The Matrix]]'', ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' and ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]''; see ''[[The Ultimate Matrix Collection]]'' (with [[Ken Wilber]], 2004)\n* ''Hope on a Tightrope: Words & Wisdom'' (2008)\n* ''Brother West: Living & Loving Out Loud'' (2009)\n* ''[[The Rich and the Rest of Us: A Poverty Manifesto]]'' (with [[Tavis Smiley]], 2012)\n* ''Pro+Agonist: The Art of Opposition'' (2012)\n* ''Black Prophetic Fire'' (2014)\n\n==Filmography==\n;Film\n*''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' (2003) as Councilor West\n*''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'' (2003) as Councilor West\n*''[[Street Fight (film)|Street Fight]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Examined Life]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Private Lives of Pippa Lee ]]'' (2009) as Don Sexton\n*''[[Bars4justice|#Bars4Justice]]'' (2015) as himself\n*''[[Chasing Trane: The John Coltrane Documentary ]]'' (2016) as himself\n*''[[No Safe Spaces]]'' (2019) as himself.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2019/11/documentary-no-safe-spaces-adam-carolla-dennis-prager-fight-free-speech-bans/ |title = In No Safe Spaces, an Odd Couple Teams up to Fight Free-Speech Bans|date = November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Television\n*\"[[What Will Happen to the Gang Next Year?]]\" (2012)\n\n==Discography==\n;Albums\n*''Sketches of My Culture'' (2001)\n*''Street Knowledge'' (2004)\n*''Never Forget: A Journey of Revelations'' (2007) <small>(with BMWMB)</small>\n\n;Guest appearances\n*[[E-40]] \u2013 \"Born in the Struggle\" from ''[[Revenue Retrievin': Overtime Shift]]'' (2011)\n*[[Bootsy Collins]] \u2013 \"Freedumb\" from ''[[Tha Funk Capital of the World]]'' (2011)\n*[[Immortal Technique]] \u2013 \"Sign of the Times\" from ''[[The Martyr (album)|The Martyr]]'' (2011)\n*[[Brother Ali]] \u2013 \"Letter to My Countrymen\" from ''[[Mourning in America and Dreaming in Color]]'' (2012)\n*[[Terence Blanchard]] \u2013 ''[[Choices (Terence Blanchard album)|Choices]]'' (2009)\n*[[Terence Blanchard]] \u2013 ''[[Breathless (Terence Blanchard album)|Breathless]]'' (2015)\n*[[Terence Blanchard]] \u2013 ''[[Live (Terence Blanchard album)|Live]]'' (2018)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Biography}}\n* [[Africana philosophy]]\n* [[American philosophy]]\n* [[Black existentialism]]\n* [[Christian left]]\n* [[List of American philosophers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/121550/cornel-wests-rise-fall-our-most-exciting-black-scholar-ghost |title=The Ghost of Cornel West |first=Michael Eric |last=Dyson |authorlink=Michael Eric Dyson |date=April 19, 2015 |journal=[[The New Republic]] }}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{IMDb name|0922002}}\n*{{Discogs artist|Cornel West}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Cornel West}}\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/cornel-west Column archive] at ''[[The Huffington Post]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Alphonse Fletcher University Professor|years=1998\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Henry Louis Gates Jr.]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Union Theological Seminary (New York City)}}\n{{Socialism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West, Cornel}}\n[[Category:20th-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Baptists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American philosophers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Baptists]]\n[[Category:Activists for African-American civil rights]]\n[[Category:African-American academics]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American philosophers]]\n[[Category:African-American studies scholars]]\n[[Category:African-American theologians]]\n[[Category:African-American writers]]\n[[Category:American Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:American Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:American civil rights activists]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American male essayists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American political activists]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political philosophers]]\n[[Category:American social commentators]]\n[[Category:Anti-corporate activists]]\n[[Category:Anti-poverty advocates]]\n[[Category:Anti-racism activists]]\n[[Category:Baptist socialists]]\n[[Category:Critical race theory]]\n[[Category:Critical theorists]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Divinity School faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:HuffPost writers and columnists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Democratic Socialists of America]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Pragmatists]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:Princeton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Four Freedoms Award]]\n[[Category:Social critics]]\n[[Category:Union Theological Seminary (New York City) faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Paris faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale University faculty]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n\n<!-- -->\n[[Category:Academics from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:Activists from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:California socialists]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma socialists]]\n[[Category:Christians from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Baptist philosophers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|African-American philosopher and political/civil rights activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{for|the residential section of Cornell University|Cornell West Campus}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name               = Cornel West\n| image              = Cornel West by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| birth_name         = Cornel Ronald West\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1953|6|2}}\n| birth_place        = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| home_town          = [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]], U.S.\n| spouse             = {{plainlist|\n* Hilda Holloman ({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1977; {{abbr|div.|divorced}})<ref>{{cite book |last1=West |first1=Cornel |last2=Ritz |first2=David |author2-link=David Ritz |year=2009 |title=Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud |location=New York |publisher=SmileyBooks |pages=95, 107 |isbn=978-1-4019-2677-9}}</ref>\n* Ramona Santiago ({{abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1981; {{abbr|div.|divorced}}&nbsp;{{circa|1986}})<ref>{{cite book |last1=West |first1=Cornel |last2=Ritz |first2=David |author2-link=David Ritz |year=2009 |title=Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud |location=New York |publisher=SmileyBooks |pages=117\u2013119, 139 |isbn=978-1-4019-2677-9}}</ref>\n* {{marriage|Elleni Gebre Amlak|1992 }}\n {{marriage|Leslie Kotkin|2016 |2018}}\n<ref>{{cite book |last=Russell |first=Dick |year=2009 |title=Black Genius: Inspirational Portraits of African-American Leaders |edition=rev. large print |location=New York |publisher=Skyhorse Publishing |page=221 |isbn=978-1-60239-369-1}}</ref>}}\n| website            = {{official URL}}\n| education          = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Princeton University]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n| thesis_title       = Ethics, Historicism and the Marxist Tradition\n| thesis_year        = 1980\n| school_tradition   = {{hlist | [[Neopragmatism]]<ref>[https://www.iep.utm.edu/pragmati/ Pragmatism \u2013 Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy]</ref> | [[existentialism]] | [[Africana philosophy]] | [[historicism]] | [[democratic socialism]] | [[radical democracy]] | [[Baptists|Baptism]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=West |first1=Cornel |last2=Ritz |first2=David |author2-link=David Ritz |year=2009 |title=Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud |location=New York |publisher=SmileyBooks |page=165 |isbn=978-1-4019-2677-9}}</ref>}}\n| influences         = {{flatlist|\n* [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]\n* [[Malcolm X]]\n* [[W.&nbsp;E.&nbsp;B. Du Bois]]\n* [[James H. Cone|James Cone]]\n* [[Karl Marx]]\n* [[Friedrich Engels]]\n* [[Richard Rorty]]\n* [[Reinhold Niebuhr]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Stone |first=Ronald H. |year=2014 |chapter=Afterword |editor-last=Weaver |editor-first=Matthew Lon |title=Applied Christian Ethics: Foundations, Economic Justice, and Politics |location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Lexington Books |page=279 |isbn=978-0-7391-9659-5}}</ref>\n* [[Sheldon Wolin]]\n* [[S\u00f8ren Kierkegaard]]\n* [[Michel Foucault]]\n* [[Paul Tillich]]\n* [[Blaise Pascal]]\n* [[Toni Morrison]]\n* [[Anton Chekhov]]\n* [[Eugene O'Neill]]\n* [[Josiah Royce]]\n* [[Simone Weil]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Schultz |first=Rick |date=June 1, 2016 |title=Challenging 'Passion' to Open Ojai Music Festival |url=https://jewishjournal.com/culture/arts_in_la/185973/ |newspaper=Jewish Journal |location=Los Angeles |publisher=Tribe Media |access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>}}\n| discipline         = {{hlist | [[African-American studies]] | [[philosophy]]}}\n| workplaces         = {{unbulleted list | [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]] | [[Yale University]] | [[Harvard University]] | [[Princeton University]] | [[Dartmouth College]]}}\n| doctoral_students  = [[Leah Hunt-Hendrix]]<ref>{{cite web |date=November 22, 2016 |title=Innovator Insights: Leah Hunt-Hendrix, Founder of Solidaire Network |url=https://medium.com/invested-impact/innovator-insights-leah-hunt-hendrix-founder-of-solidaire-network-8e30f81ed48 |website=Invested Impact |access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| main_interests     = {{hlist | [[Political philosophy]] | [[philosophy of religion]] | [[ethics]] | [[race (classification of human beings)|race]] | [[democracy]] | [[liberation theology]]}}\n| notable_works      = {{unbulleted list | ''[[Race Matters]]'' (1994) | ''Democracy Matters'' (2004)}}\n}}\n'''Cornel Ronald West''' (born June 2, 1953) is an American philosopher, political activist, social critic, author, and [[public intellectual]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://inthesetimes.com/article/1392/cornel_west_public_intellectual|title=Cornel West: Public Intellectual|date=November 4, 2004|first=Salim|last=Muwakkil|accessdate=May 21, 2017|journal=In These Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitman.edu/newsroom/well-known-public-intellectual-cornel-west-at-whitman-december-4|title=Well-Known Public Intellectual Cornel West at Whitman December 4|date=November 19, 2003|first=Lenel|last=Parish|accessdate=May 21, 2017|publisher=[[Whitman College]]}}</ref> \nThe son of a [[Baptist]] minister, West focuses on the role of [[Race (classification of human beings)|race]], [[gender]], and [[class (social)|class]] in American society and the means by which people act and react to their \"radical conditionedness\". A [[radical democracy|radical democrat]] and [[Democratic socialism|democratic socialist]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagodsa.org/CornelWest.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-11-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161217170932/http://www.chicagodsa.org/CornelWest.html |archivedate=December 17, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsausa.org/cornel_west|title=Cornel West, DSA Honorary Chair|access-date=November 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419052144/http://www.dsausa.org/cornel_west|archive-date=April 19, 2018|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> West draws intellectual contributions from multiple traditions, including [[Christianity]], the [[black church]], [[Marxism]], [[neopragmatism]], and [[transcendentalism]].<ref name=\"pragmatic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pragmatism.org/research/cont_prag_books.htm#west |title=Contemporary \u00ab Research Pragmatism Cybrary |publisher=Pragmatism.org |accessdate=2015-04-23}}</ref><ref name=\"blackbio\">\"Cornel Ronald West\". ''Contemporary Black Biography'', Volume 33. Ed. Ashyia Henderson. Gale Group, 2002. Reproduced in Biography Resource Center. Farmington Hills, Mich.: The Gale Group. 2004.</ref><ref>\"Cornel West y la pol\u00edtica de conversi\u00f3n\". Thomas Ward. ''Resistencia cultural: La naci\u00f3n en el ensayo de las Am\u00e9ricas''. Lima: Universidad Ricardo Palma, 2004, pp. 344\u2013348.</ref><ref>Nishikawa, Kinohi. \"Cornel West.\" ''The Greenwood Encyclopedia of African American Literature''. Ed. Hans Ostrom and J. David Macey, Jr. Westport, CT: Greenwood Press, 2005. 1714\u201318.</ref> Among his most influential books are ''[[Race Matters]]'' (1994) and ''Democracy Matters'' (2004).\n\nWest is an outspoken voice in [[left-wing politics in the United States]], and as such has been critical of members of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], including former President [[Barack Obama]] and [[Hillary Clinton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2014/08/24/cornel_west_he_posed_as_a_progressive_and_turned_out_to_be_counterfeit_we_ended_up_with_a_wall_street_presidency_a_drone_presidency/|date=August 24, 2014|title=Cornel West: \"He posed as a progressive and turned out to be counterfeit. We ended up with a Wall Street presidency, a drone presidency\"|first=Thomas|last=Frank|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3453797/cornel-west-calls-obama-administration-a-drone-presidency/|title=Cornel West: Obama Administration is a 'Drone Presidency'|date=October 2, 2014|accessdate=May 21, 2017|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/book-party/wp/2015/01/19/has-obama-embodied-martin-luther-king-jr-s-legacy-or-betrayed-it/|title=Cornel West channels Martin Luther King Jr. to criticize Obama|first=Carlos|last=Lozada|date=January 19, 2015|accessdate=May 21, 2017|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> He has held professorships and fellowships at [[Harvard University]], [[Dartmouth College]], [[Princeton University]], [[Yale University]], [[Pepperdine University]], [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]], and the [[University of Paris]] during his career.<ref>[https://montgomery.dartmouth.edu/cornel-west Dartmouth.edu] {{webarchive |url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:tR2m5dKz7YoJ:https://montgomery.dartmouth.edu/cornel-west+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us |date=September 17, 2019 }}</ref> He is also a frequent commentator on politics and social issues in many media outlets.<ref>[http://www.cornelwest.com/about.html Cornelwest.com] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703022827/http://www.cornelwest.com/about.html |date=July 3, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 through 2013, West co-hosted a radio program with [[Tavis Smiley]], called ''Smiley and West''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://targetmarketnews.com/storyid10181301.htm|title=Tavis Smiley, Cornell West ending their public radio show in December|work=targetmarketnews.com|accessdate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://oppressionmonitor.us/2013/12/29/smiley-west-noam-chomsky-final-smiley-west/|title=Smiley and West \u2013 Noam Chomsky: The Final Smiley and West|work=Oppression Monitor Daily|accessdate=April 26, 2015|date=December 29, 2013}}</ref> He has also been featured in several documentaries, and made appearances in Hollywood films such as ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' and ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'', providing commentary for both films. West has also made several [[spoken word]] and [[hip hop]] albums, and due to his work, has been named [[MTV]]'s Artist of the Week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2291762/artist-of-the-week-dr-cornel-west//|title=Artist Of The Week: Dr. Cornel West by Tamar Anitai |work=MTV|accessdate=April 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nWest was born on June 2, 1953, in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma|Tulsa]], [[Oklahoma]],<ref name=\"influx\">{{cite web |url= http://influx.uoregon.edu/1998/west/index.html |title= Prisoner of Hope |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020209041340/http://influx.uoregon.edu/1998/west/index.html |archivedate=February 9, 2002 |accessdate=November 4, 2015 |last=Elder |first= Robert |authorlink=Robert K. Elder |year= 1998 |work=inFlux |publisher= University of Oregon School of Journalism and Communication}}</ref> and grew up in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]], where he graduated from [[John F. Kennedy High School (Sacramento, California)|John F. Kennedy High School]]. His mother, Irene (Bias), was a teacher and principal, and his father, Clifton Louis West Jr., was a [[general contractor]] for the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.enotes.com/topics/cornel-west |title=Cornel West Biography |publisher=Enotes.com |accessdate=2015-04-23}}</ref> Irene B. West Elementary School in [[Elk Grove, California|Elk Grove]], California, is named for his mother.<ref>{{cite journal |last=smitty |first=Fahizah |title=Opening Doors: Irene West Gave Her All as a Teacher and Principal, Now, a New School Honors Her Name and Hard Work |journal=Sacramento Bee |date=June 4, 1999 }}</ref>\n\nAs a young man, West marched in [[civil rights]] demonstrations and organized protests demanding black studies courses at his high school, where he was class president. He later wrote that, in his youth, he admired \"the sincere black militancy of [[Malcolm X]], the defiant rage of the [[Black Panther Party]], and the livid [[black theology]] of [[James H. Cone]].\"<ref>{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/?id=Kk6ovUWs02AC&pg=PA3 |title= The Cornel West Reader |isbn= 978-0-465-09110-2 |author1= West, Cornel |date= August 13, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 1970, after graduating from high school, he enrolled at [[Harvard College]] and took classes from the philosophers [[Robert Nozick]] and [[Stanley Cavell]]. In 1973, West graduated from Harvard ''[[Latin honors|magna cum laude]]'' in Near Eastern languages and civilization.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bc.edu/bc_org/rvp/pubaf/chronicle/v13/o21/postings.html |title=Author Cornel West to Speak in Robsham Theater Oct. 30 |date=October 21, 2004 |publisher=The [[Boston College]] Chronicle |accessdate=January 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100602022035/http://www.bc.edu/bc_org/rvp/pubaf/chronicle/v13/o21/postings.html |archive-date=June 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He credits Harvard with exposing him to a broader range of ideas, influenced by his professors as well as the Black Panther Party. West says his Christianity prevented him from joining the BPP, instead choosing to work in local breakfast, prison, and church programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.democracynow.org/2009/9/30/dr_cornel_west_on_his_new |title=Dr. Cornel West Releases Long-Awaited Memoir, \"Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud\" |author=Goodman, Amy |date=September 30, 2009 |work=Democracy Now |accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref> After completing his undergraduate work at Harvard, West enrolled at [[Princeton University]] where he received a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] (PhD) degree in 1980, becoming the first African American to graduate from Princeton with a PhD degree in philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/faultlines/2010/03/201031162433794100.html |title=Cornel West |publisher=Aljazeera.com |date=2010-03-11 |accessdate=2015-04-23}}</ref> At Princeton, West was heavily influenced by [[Richard Rorty]]'s [[neopragmatism]].<ref name=Mendieta/> Rorty remained a close friend and colleague of West's for many years following West's graduation. The title of West's [[dissertation]] was ''Ethics, Historicism and the Marxist Tradition'',<ref>{{cite document |title= ''Ethics, historicism and the Marxist tradition'' |id = {{ProQuest|303076528}}}}</ref> which was later revised and published under the title ''The Ethical Dimensions of Marxist Thought''.<ref name=Mendieta>{{cite book |last=Mendieta |first=Eduardo |title=Global Fragments: Globalizations, Latinamericanisms, and Critical Theory |year=2007 |publisher=State University of New York Press |location=Albany, New York |isbn=978-0-7914-7257-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CycoIHOtyhYC&pg=PA173 |page=173 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Academic appointments ===\n\nIn his late-20s, he returned to Harvard as a [[W.&nbsp;E.&nbsp;B. Du Bois]] [[Fellow]] before becoming an assistant professor at [[Union Theological Seminary in the City of New York]]. In 1984, he went to [[Yale Divinity School]] in what eventually became a joint appointment in [[American studies]]. While at Yale, he participated in campus protests for a clerical labor union and [[divestment]] from [[apartheid]] South Africa. One of the protests resulted in his being arrested and jailed. As punishment, the university administration canceled his leave for the spring term in 1987, leading him to commute from Yale in [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], [[Connecticut]], where he was teaching two classes, across the Atlantic Ocean to the [[University of Paris]].<ref name=\"blackbio\"/>\n\nHe then returned to Union Theological Seminary <!-- restore when you can find a source: and taught at [[Haverford College]] in Pennsylvania --> for one year before going to Princeton to become a professor of religion and director of the Program in [[African American studies|African-American Studies]] from 1988 to 1994.<ref name=blackbio/> After Princeton, he accepted an appointment as professor of African-American studies at Harvard University, with a joint appointment at the [[Harvard Divinity School]].<ref name=Aaseng>{{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Aaseng |editor-first=Nathan |encyclopedia=African-American Religious Leaders |title=Cornel West |year=2003 |publisher=Facts on File |location=New York |isbn=0-8160-4878-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/africanamericanr00aase_0/page/237 237] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/africanamericanr00aase_0/page/237 }} {{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref> West taught one of the university's most popular courses, an introductory class on African-American studies.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-08-16/features/0208160010_1_cornel-west-president-of-harvard-university-prostate-surgery |title=Cornel West's difficult road to Princeton |last=Duke |first=Lynn |date=August 16, 2002 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=October 22, 2011 }}</ref> In 1998, he was appointed the first [[Alphonse Fletcher]] [[Endowed professor|University Professor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aaas.fas.harvard.edu/about/moments |title=Other Key Moments in the Department |publisher=Department of African and African American Studies, Harvard University |accessdate=October 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006185200/http://aaas.fas.harvard.edu/about/moments |archivedate=October 6, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> West utilized this new position to teach in not only African-American studies, but also in divinity, religion, and philosophy.<ref name=Aaseng/> West left Harvard after a widely publicized<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/16/us/defector-indignant-at-president-of-harvard.html|title=Defector Indignant at President of Harvard|first=Pam Belluck With Jacques|last=Steinberg|date=April 16, 2002|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> dispute with then-President [[Lawrence Summers]] in 2002.<ref>Cornel West. Brother West: Living and Loving Out Loud. A Memoir. Hay House, Inc. {{ISBN|978-1401921903}}. 1985, pp. 216\u2013230</ref> That year, West returned to Princeton, where he helped create \"one of the world\u2019s leading centers for African-American studies\" according to [[Shirley Tilghman]], Princeton's president in 2011.<ref name=NYT2011>{{cite news|last1=Goodstein|first1=Laurie|title=Cornel West to Take a Job in New York|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/17/nyregion/cornel-west-returning-to-union-theological-seminary.html?_r=0|accessdate=26 August 2014|work=New York Times|date=November 16, 2011}}</ref>  In 2012, West left Princeton and returned to the institution where he began his teaching career, Union Theological Seminary.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/17/nyregion/cornel-west-returning-to-union-theological-seminary.html | work=The New York Times | first=Laurie | last=Goodstein | title=Cornel West Returning to Union Theological Seminary | date=November 16, 2011}}</ref> His departure from Princeton, unlike his departure from Harvard, was quite amicable. As of 2017, he continues to teach occasional courses at Princeton in an [[emeritus]] capacity as the Class of 1943 University Professor in the Center for African American Studies.<ref name=NYT2011 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://religion.princeton.edu/people/faculty/emeriti-faculty/cornel-west/|title=Cornel West \u2013 Department of Religion|author=|date=August 25, 2016|website=princeton.edu|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe recipient of more than 20 honorary degrees and an [[American Book Award]],<ref name=\"pragmatic\"/> he has written or contributed to over twenty published books. West is a long-time member of the [[Democratic Socialists of America]], for which he now serves as an honorary chair.<ref name=blackbio/> He is also a co-founder of the [[Network of Spiritual Progressives]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://spiritualprogressives.org/newsite/?page_id=33 |title=NSP Co-Founders |publisher=Network of Spiritual Progressives |accessdate=October 22, 2011 }}</ref> West is on the advisory board of the [[International Bridges to Justice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibj.org/about-us/directors-and-advisors/ |title=Board of Directors and Advisors |publisher=International Bridges to Justice |accessdate=October 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126142945/http://www.ibj.org/about-us/directors-and-advisors/ |archivedate=November 26, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he received a special recognition from the [[World Cultural Council]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Special Recognitions 2008 |publisher=[[World Cultural Council]] |url=http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/memories-ceremony2008-SpecialRecognitions.php |accessdate=August 19, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105183105/http://www.consejoculturalmundial.org/memories-ceremony2008-SpecialRecognitions.php |archivedate=November 5, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nWest is also a member of [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] fraternity and its [[World Policy Council]], a [[think tank]] whose purpose is to expand Alpha Phi Alpha's involvement in politics and social and current policy to encompass international concerns.<ref name=\"WPC#5\">{{cite journal|first=Horace |last=Dawson |authorlink=Horace Dawson |author2=[[Edward Brooke]], [[Henry Ponder]], Vinton R. Anderson, [[Bobby William Austin]], [[Ron Dellums]], [[Kenton Keith (diplomat)|Kenton Keith]], Huel D. Perkins, [[Charles B. Rangel|Charles Rangel]], Clathan McClain Ross, and Cornel West |title=The Centenary Report of the Alpha Phi Alpha World Policy Council |publisher=Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity |date=July 2006 |url=http://www.alpha-phi-alpha.com/Resources/ImageFile/File/image/WPC06-WEB.pdf |accessdate=May 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090225132901/http://www.alpha-phi-alpha.com/Resources/ImageFile/File/image/WPC06-WEB.pdf |archivedate=February 25, 2009 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nWest has been widely cited in the popular press.<ref>{{cite document |title=Cornel West Quitting Harvard |last1=Fletcher |first1=Michael A. |last2=Ferdinand |first2=Pamela |date=April 13, 2002 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|409336618}}}}</ref> His scholarship has been criticized as well as praised; ''[[The New Republic]]'' literary editor [[Leon Wieseltier]] called West's writing \"sectarian, humorless, pedantic and self-endeared\".<ref>Wieseltier, quoted in {{cite book |ref=harv |last1=Wood |first1=Mark David |title=Cornel West and the Politics of Prophetic Pragmatism |date=2000 |publisher=University of Illinois Press |isbn=0-25-202578-4 |page=4 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Cornel_West_and_the_Politics_of_Propheti.html?id=RVdQ0mhiapUC&q=wieseltier}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Harvard announced that West would be leaving Union Theological Seminary to hold a joint nontenured appointment at the [[Harvard Divinity School]] and the Harvard Department of African and African-American Studies as Professor of the Practice of Public Philosophy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aaas.fas.harvard.edu/people/cornel-r-west|title=Cornel R. West|author=|date=|website=aaas.fas.harvard.edu|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hds.harvard.edu/people/cornel-r-west|title=Cornel R. West|author=|date=|website=hds.harvard.edu|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/20/us/cornel-west-harvard.html|title=Cornel West Will Return to Teach at Harvard|last=Seelye|first=Katharine Q.|date=2016-11-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-03-25|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Entertainment career===\nWest appears as Councillor West in both ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' and ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'' and also provides the voice for this character in the video game ''[[Enter the Matrix]]''.<ref name=agger>Agger, Michael. [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/18/movies/film-and-the-oscar-for-best-scholar.html FILM; And the Oscar for Best Scholar . . .]. ''The New York Times''. May 18, 2003. Retrieved March 7, 2011.</ref> In addition, West provides philosophical commentary on all three Matrix films in [[The Ultimate Matrix Collection]], along with the [[Integral theory (Ken Wilber)|integral theorist]] [[Ken Wilber]].<ref>Pratt, Doug. [http://www.allbusiness.com/services/motion-pictures/4819022-1.html The Ultimate Matrix Collection]. ''The Hollywood Reporter'' via AllBusiness. December 6, 2004. Retrieved March 7, 2011. {{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe has made several appearances in documentary films also, such as the 2008 film ''[[Examined Life]]'', a documentary featuring several academics discussing philosophy in real-world contexts. West, \"driving through Manhattan,&nbsp;... compares philosophy to jazz and blues, reminding us how intense and invigorating a life of the mind can be.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Examined Life (2008) \u2013 Plot Summary |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1279083/plotsummary}}</ref> He also appears in conversation with [[Bill Withers]] in the Bill Withers documentary, ''[[Still Bill (film)|Still Bill]]''.\n\nWest has made frequent appearances on the political talk show ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Real Time with Bill Maher: Full Cast and Crew |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0350448/fullcredits#cast |accessdate=April 21, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nA character based on West and events in his career appeared in the ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' episode \"[[Anti-Thesis]]\", significant for introducing the recurring villain character Nicole Wallace.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://gseis.ucla.edu/faculty/kellner/essays/academicscoundrls.pdf \n |title=Academic Scandals and the Broadcast Media \n |author1=Rhonda Hammer \n |author2=Douglas Kellner \n |publisher=Gseis.ucla.edu \n |accessdate=2015-04-23 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626082720/http://www.gseis.ucla.edu/faculty/kellner/essays/academicscoundrls.pdf \n |archivedate=June 26, 2010 \n |df=mdy \n}} \n</ref>\n\nIn May 2012, West guest-starred in the sixth season of the American television comedy series ''[[30 Rock]]'', \"[[What Will Happen to the Gang Next Year?]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/30-rock-what-will-happen-to-the-gang-next-year-73998|title=30 Rock: \"What Will Happen To The Gang Next Year?\"|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|first=Meredith|last=Blake|date=May 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn the musical front, West recorded a recitation of [[John Mellencamp]]'s song \"Jim Crow\" for inclusion on the singer's [[box set]] ''[[On the Rural Route 7609]]'' in 2009.<ref name=princetonian/>\n\nIn 2010, he completed recording with the Cornel West Theory, a [[hip hop]] band endorsed by West.<ref name=princetonian>Han, Lisa. [http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/2010/02/04/24984/ Cornel West Theory] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414134335/http://www.dailyprincetonian.com/2010/02/04/24984/ |date=April 14, 2010 }}. ''Daily Princetonian''. February 4, 2010. Retrieved March 7, 2011.</ref> He has also released several hip-hop/soul/spoken word albums. In 2001, West released his first album, ''Sketches of My Culture''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/aponline/20011106/aponline142029_000.htm|title=Harvard Professor Makes Hip-Hop CD|work=[[Washington Post]]|first=Audie N.|last=Cornish|date=November 6, 2001|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> ''Street Knowledge'' followed in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastbayexpress.com/oakland/cornel-west/Content?oid=1073599|title=Cornel West \u2013 Street Knowledge|work=[[East Bay Express]]|first=Rachel|last=Swan|date=April 21, 2004|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref> In 2007, West released ''Never Forget: A Journey of Revelations'', his third album which included collaborations with the likes of [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Jill Scott]], [[Andre 3000]], [[KRS-One]], and the late [[Gerald Levert]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2007/09/06/62046-cd-review-cornel-west/|title=CD Review: Cornel West|work=[[Tucson Citizen]]|first=Brett|last=Johnson|date=September 6, 2007|accessdate=October 21, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011022753/http://tucsoncitizen.com/morgue/2007/09/06/62046-cd-review-cornel-west/|archive-date=October 11, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> West appeared on [[Immortal Technique]]'s song \"Sign of the Times\", which appeared on the 2011 album ''[[The Martyr (album)|The Martyr]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.citypages.com/gimmenoise/2011/10/immortal_technique.php |title=Immortal Technique talks about his new free album The Martyr and Occupy MN |work=[[City Pages]] |first=Rebecca |last=McDonald |date=October 27, 2011 |accessdate=October 21, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529211214/http://blogs.citypages.com/gimmenoise/2011/10/immortal_technique.php |archivedate=May 29, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref> In 2012, he was featured on [[Brother Ali]]'s song \"Letter to My Countrymen\", which appeared on the album ''[[Mourning in America and Dreaming in Color]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/16941-brother-ali-mourning-in-america-and-dreaming-in-color/|title=Brother Ali: Mourning In America and Dreaming In Color|work=[[Pitchfork Media]]|first=Nate|last=Patrin|date=September 19, 2012|accessdate=October 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, [[Robert P. George]] and West participated in an \"assembly series\" discussion at [[Washington University in St. Louis]] titled \"Liberal Arts Education: What\u2019s The Point?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://humanities.wustl.edu/events/liberal-arts-education-what%E2%80%99s-point-cornel-west-robert-george-conversation|title=Liberal Arts Education: What's The Point? Cornel West & Robert George in Conversation|date=2019-03-07|website=Center for the Humanities|language=en|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\nHis voice can be downloaded for directional guidance purposes as a downloadable option on some personal GPS-navigation device models by company [[TomTom]].\n\n==Dispute with Lawrence Summers==\nIn 2000, the economist and former US Treasury Secretary [[Lawrence Summers]] became president of Harvard. Soon after, Summers held a private meeting with West, where he reportedly rebuked West for missing too many classes, contributing to [[grade inflation]], neglecting serious scholarship, and spending too much time on his economically profitable projects.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Who is Cornel West? |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/fyi/teachers.ednews/01/10/west.harvard.ap/ |publisher=[[CNN|Cable News Network]] |date= January 10, 2002 |accessdate=January 21, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071226113730/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/fyi/teachers.ednews/01/10/west.harvard.ap/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate=December 26, 2007}}</ref> Summers reportedly suggested that West produce an academic book befitting his professorial position, as his recent output had consisted primarily of co-written and edited volumes. According to some reports, Summers also objected to West's production of a CD, the critically panned ''Sketches of My Culture'', and to his political campaigning, including an alleged three weeks to promote [[Bill Bradley]]'s [[Democratic Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2000|presidential]] campaign.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jacques |last=Steinberg |authorlink=Jacques Steinberg |title=At Odds With Harvard President, Black-Studies Stars Eye Princeton |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F06E4D71F31F93AA15751C1A9679C8B63 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |location=New York City |date=November 29, 2001 |accessdate=January 21, 2008}}</ref> West contended he had missed only one class during his tenure at Harvard \"in order to give a keynote address at a Harvard-sponsored conference on AIDS.\" Summers also allegedly suggested that since West held the rank of [[Harvard University Professor]] and thus reported directly to the President, he should meet with Summers regularly to discuss the progress of his academic production.<ref name=\"indignant\">{{cite news |first=Pam |last=Belluck |author2=Jacques Steinberg |title=Defector Indignant at President of Harvard |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0DE6DB113CF935A25757C0A9649C8B63 |work=The New York Times |publisher=The New York Times Company |location=New York City |date=April 16, 2002 |accessdate=January 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nSummers refused to comment on the details of his conversation with West, except to express hope that West would remain at Harvard. Soon after, West was hospitalized for [[prostate cancer]]. West noted that Summers failed to send him get-well wishes until weeks after his surgery, whereas newly installed Princeton president [[Shirley Tilghman]] had contacted him frequently before and after his treatment.<ref name=\"indignant\" />\n\nIn 2002 West left Harvard University to return to Princeton. West lashed out at Summers in public interviews, calling him \"the [[Ariel Sharon]] of higher education\" on NPR's ''[[The Tavis Smiley Show|Tavis Smiley Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/about/press/020415.cwest.html |title=Cornel West Outlines \"Pull toward Princeton\" and \"Push from Harvard\" in Exclusive Interview with NPR's Tavis Smiley |publisher=Npr.org |date=January 7, 2002 |accessdate=March 7, 2011}}</ref> In response to these remarks, five Princeton faculty members, led by professor of molecular biology Jacques Robert Fresco, said they looked with \"strong disfavor upon his characterization\" of Summers and that \"such an analogy carries innuendoes and implications&nbsp;... that many on the Princeton faculty find highly inappropriate, indeed repugnant and intolerable.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Cornel West's Analogy |author=Jacques R. Fresco |newspaper=The New York Times |date=April 24, 2002 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/24/opinion/l-cornel-west-s-analogy-697680.html?pagewanted=1 |url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n[[Harvard University]]'s undergraduate student newspaper, ''[[The Harvard Crimson]]'', suggested in October 2002 that the premise of the ''[[Law and Order: Criminal Intent]]'' episode \"[[Anti-Thesis]]\" was based on West's conflicts with Summers.<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell |first=Andrew C. |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/printerfriendly.aspx?ref=254638 |title=Ripped from Harvard Headlines &#124; News &#124; The Harvard Crimson |publisher=Thecrimson.com |date=October 16, 2002 |accessdate=March 7, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013164830/http://www.thecrimson.com/printerfriendly.aspx?ref=254638 |archivedate=October 13, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n\n===Views on race in the United States===\nWest has called the US a \"racist patriarchal\" nation where [[white supremacy]] continues to define everyday life. \"White America\", he writes, \"has been historically weak-willed in ensuring racial justice and has continued to resist fully accepting the humanity of blacks.\" This has resulted, he says, in the creation of many \"degraded and oppressed people hungry for identity, meaning, and self-worth.\" West attributes most of the black community's problems to \"existential angst derive[d] from the lived experience of ontological wounds and emotional scars inflicted by white supremacist beliefs and images permeating U.S. society and culture.\"<ref>Cornel West, ''Race Matters'', p. 27, 2001 edition, {{ISBN|978-0-8070-0972-7}}</ref>\n\nIn West's view, the [[September 11 attacks]] gave white Americans a glimpse of what it means to be a black person in the United States\u2014feeling \"unsafe, unprotected, subject to random violence, and hatred\" for who they are.<ref name=\"democracy matters\">Cornel West, ''Democracy Matters,'' p. 20, 2004, {{ISBN|0-14-303583-5}}</ref> \"The ugly terrorist attacks on innocent civilians on 9/11\", he said, \"plunged the whole country into the blues.\"<ref name=\"democracy matters\"/>\n\nWest was arrested on October 13, 2014, while protesting against the [[shooting of Michael Brown]] and participating in [[Ferguson October]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornel West arrested; video of #FergusonOctober from Fusion's Tim Pool|url=http://fusion.net/video/21051/unrest-in-st-louis/|website=Fusion.net|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cornel West in Ferguson: 'I Came Here to Go to Jail'|url=http://www.truthdig.com/avbooth/item/cornel_west_in_ferguson_i_came_here_to_go_to_jail_20141013|website=Truth Dig|publisher=Truth Dig|accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> and again on August 10, 2015, while demonstrating outside a courthouse in [[St. Louis]] on the one-year anniversary of Brown's death.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/cornel-west-dozens-arrested-missouri-protests-article-1.2320829 |title=Cornel West among dozens of protesters arrested at St. Louis courthouse as state of emergency declared in Missouri |first1=Cameron |last1=Joseph |first2=Corky |last2=Siemaszko |date=August 10, 2015 |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |accessdate=August 11, 2015 }}</ref> The 2015 documentary film ''[[Bars4justice|#Bars4Justice]]'' includes footage of West demonstrating and being arrested in Ferguson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nation19.com/nation19s-new-short-film-filmed-in-ferguson-set-to-premier-in-phoenix/ |title=Filmmakers bring Ferguson to Phoenix's Hip Hop community\u2026 Sheriff Arpaio not invited |date=September 30, 2015 |work=[[Nation19]] |accessdate=April 23, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\n[[File:Cornel West & Robert P. George (28154741749).jpg|right|thumb|West (left) with [[Robert P. George]] (right) in 2018]]\nWest has described himself as a \"non-[[Marxist]] socialist\" (partly because he does not view Marxism and Christianity as reconcilable)<ref>{{cite book |last=West |first=Cornel |title=The Cornel West Reader |year=1999 |publisher=Basic Civitas Books |location=New York |isbn=0-465-09109-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bNJD8g1e-QQC&pg=PA13 |page=13 }}</ref> and serves as honorary chair of the [[Democratic Socialists of America]], which he has described as \"the first multiracial, socialist organization close enough to my politics that I could join\".<ref name=blackbio/> He also described himself as a \"radical democrat, suspicious of all forms of authority\" in the ''Matrix''-themed documentary ''The Burly Man Chronicles''.<ref>{{cite video |people=Cornel West |title=[[The Ultimate Matrix Collection]] }}</ref>\n\nWest believes that \"the overthrow of [[Saddam Hussein]]'s ugly totalitarian regime was desirable,\"<ref>Cornel West, ''Democracy Matters,'' p. 58, 2004, {{ISBN|0-14-303583-5}}</ref> but that the [[war in Iraq]] was the result of \"dishonest manipulation\" on the part of the Bush administration.<ref>Cornel West, ''Democracy Matters,'' p. 101, 2004, {{ISBN|0-14-303583-5}}</ref> He asserts that Bush administration [[war hawk|hawks]] \"are not simply conservative elites and right-wing ideologues\", but rather are \"evangelical nihilists&nbsp;\u2013 drunk with power and driven by grand delusions of American domination of the world\". He adds, \"We are [now] experiencing the sad gangsterization of America, an unbridled grasp at power, wealth, and status.\" Viewing capitalism as the root cause of these alleged American lusts, West warns, \"[[market fundamentalism|Free-market fundamentalism]] trivializes the concern for public interest. It puts fear and insecurity in the hearts of anxiety-ridden workers. It also makes money-driven, poll-obsessed elected officials deferential to corporate goals of profit \u2013 often at the cost of the common good.\"<ref>[http://www.theglobalist.com/StoryId.aspx?StoryId=4262 Theglobalist.com]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203073821/http://www.theglobalist.com/StoryId.aspx?StoryId=4262 |date=December 3, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nWest has been involved with such projects as the [[Million Man March]] and [[Russell Simmons]]'s Hip-Hop Summit, and worked with such public figures as [[Louis Farrakhan]]<ref name=\"influx\"/> and [[Al Sharpton]], whose 2004 presidential campaign West advised.<ref>{{cite document |title=Cornel West, Cloaked in Street Smarts |last=Givhan |first=Robin |authorlink=Robin Givhan |date=January 25, 2002 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|409271497}}}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, West worked as a senior advisor to [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] [[President of the United States|presidential]] candidate [[Bill Bradley]]. When Bradley lost in the primaries, West became a prominent endorser of [[Ralph Nader]], even speaking at some Nader rallies. Some [[United States Green Party|Greens]] sought to draft West to run as a presidential candidate in 2004. West declined, citing his active participation in the [[Al Sharpton]] campaign. West, along with other prominent Nader 2000 supporters, signed the \"Vote to Stop Bush\" statement urging progressive voters in swing states to vote for [[John Kerry]], despite strong disagreements with many of Kerry's policies.<ref>\"Senators Hillary Clinton and John Kerry are exemplary paternalistic nihilists... Their centrist or conservative policies... are opportunistic efforts to satisfy centrist or conservative constituencies.\" Cornel West, ''Democracy Matters,'' p. 35-36, 2004, {{ISBN|0-14-303583-5}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2002 West and Rabbi [[Michael Lerner (rabbi)|Michael Lerner]] performed civil disobedience by sitting in the street in front of the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] \"in solidarity with suffering Palestinian and Israeli brothers and sisters.\" West said, \"We must keep in touch with the humanity of both sides.\"<ref>{{cite document |title=Peace Demonstrators Arrested, Without Much Conviction |last=Montgomery |first=David |date=April 12, 2002 |work=The Washington Post |id = {{ProQuest|409255662}}}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://supportcom.com/PEP/www.pepeace.org/current_reprints/10/Thoughts_On_Antisemitism.htm |title=Thoughts on Anti-Semitism |publisher=Supportcom.com |date=December 6, 2005 |accessdate=March 7, 2011}}</ref> In May 2007 West joined a demonstration against \"injustices faced by the Palestinian people resulting from the Israeli occupation\" and \"to bring attention to this 40-year travesty of justice\". In 2011, West called on the [[University of Arizona]] to divest from companies profiting from the [[Israeli occupation of the Palestinian territories]].<ref>[http://nomoredeaths.org/University-of-Arizona-NMD/cornel-west-ua-letter.html Nomordeaths.org] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719162402/http://nomoredeaths.org/University-of-Arizona-NMD/cornel-west-ua-letter.html |date=July 19, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWest also serves as co-chair of the [[Tikkun Community]]. He co-chaired the National Parenting Organization's Task Force on Parent Empowerment and participated in President [[Bill Clinton]]'s National Conversation on Race. He has publicly endorsed ''[[In These Times]]'' magazine by calling it: \"The most creative and challenging news magazine of the American left\". He is also a contributing editor for ''[[Sojourners]]'' magazine.\n\nWest supports [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) in its Kentucky Fried Cruelty campaign, aimed at eliminating what PETA describes as [[KFC]]'s inhumane treatment of chickens. West is quoted on PETA flyers: \"Although most people don't know chickens as well as they know cats and dogs, chickens are interesting individuals with personalities and interests every bit as developed as the dogs and cats with whom many of us share our lives.\"\n\nIn 2008, West contributed his insights on the current global issue of modernized slavery and [[human trafficking]] in the documentary ''Call+Response''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.callandresponse.com |title=Call + Response |publisher=Callandresponse.com |accessdate=March 7, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223190730/http://www.callandresponse.com/ |archive-date=February 23, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> West is a member of the [[Campaign for Peace and Democracy]].\n\nIn 2011, West addressed his frustration about some critics of the [[Occupy Wall Street]], who remark about the movement's lack of a clear and unified message. West replied by saying:\n<blockquote>\nIt's impossible to translate the issue of the greed of Wall Street into one demand, or two demands. We're talking about a democratic awakening...you're talking about raising political consciousness so it spills over all parts of the country, so people can begin to see what's going on through a set of different lens, and then you begin to highlight what the more detailed demands would be. Because in the end we're really talking about what [[Martin Luther King Jr.|Martin King]] would call a revolution: A transfer of power from [[Business oligarch|oligarch]]s to everyday people of all colors. And that is a step by step process.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cornel West on Occupy Wall Street: It's the Makings of a U.S. Autumn Responding to the Arab Spring|url=http://www.democracynow.org/blog/2011/9/29/cornel_west_on_occupy_wall_street_its_the_makings_of_a_us_autumn_responding_to_the_arab_spring|publisher=[[Democracy Now]]|date=September 29, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> \n</blockquote>\n\nOn October 16, 2011, West was in [[Washington, DC]], participating in the [[Occupy D.C.]] protests on the steps of the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] over the court's decision in the ''[[Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission]]'' case the previous year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/guest-voices/post/dr-cornel-west-honors-dr-martin-luther-king-jr-by-going-to-jail/2011/10/17/gIQA9oLRrL_blog.html |title=Dr. Cornel West honors Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. by going to jail |author=Thisltethwaite, Susan Brooks |date=October 17, 2011 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref> Five days later, he was arrested during an Occupy Wall Street protest in [[Harlem]] against the New York Police Department's [[stop and frisk]] policy.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://newsfeed.time.com/2011/10/22/cornel-west-arrested-again-at-occupy-protest/ |title=Cornel West Arrested Again at Occupy Protest |author=Carbone, Nick |date=October 22, 2011 |journal=Time |accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, West co-initiated the Stop Mass Incarceration Network, a project of the [[Revolutionary Communist Party USA]]. Later that year, he and RCP chairman [[Bob Avakian]] took part in a filmed discussion on \"Religion and Revolution\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://revcom.us/film|title=Revolution and Religion: The Fight for Emancipation and the Role of Religion|website=Revcom.us|accessdate=December 29, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, West was one of a group of interfaith, multiracial clergy who took part in a counter-protest at the [[Unite the Right Rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]], [[Virginia]]; West averred that [[Antifa (U.S.)|Antifa]] had saved their lives.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.democracynow.org/2017/8/14/cornel_west_rev_toni_blackmon_clergy |title=Cornel West & Rev. Traci Blackmon: Clergy in Charlottesville Were Trapped by Torch-Wielding Nazis |date=August 14, 2017 |website=Democracy Now! |access-date=August 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===Views on Barack Obama===\nWest has often spoken about the lack of adequate black leadership and how it leads to doubt within black communities as to their political potential to ensure change.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Black Popular Culture|last=Wallace|first=Michele|publisher=Bay Press|year=1992|isbn=978-1-56584-459-9|location=Seattle|pages=45}}</ref> Cornel West publicly supported [[Democratic Party presidential candidates, 2008|2008 Democratic presidential candidate]] Senator [[Barack Obama]]. He spoke to over 1,000 of his supporters at the [[Apollo Theater]] in [[Harlem]], on November 29, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stacy|last=Parker Aab|title=Obama, Race, and the Right Side of History|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/stacy-parker-aab/obama-race-and-the-righ_b_74871.html|work=The Huffington News|publisher=HuffingtonPost.com, Inc.|date=October 30, 2007|accessdate=January 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWest criticized President Barack Obama when he won the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] in 2009, saying that it would be difficult for Obama to be \"a war president with a peace prize\". West further retracted his support for Obama in an April 2011 interview, stating that Obama is \"a black mascot of Wall Street oligarchs and a black muppet of corporate plutocrats. And now he has become head of the American killing machine and is proud of it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/10/10/cornel-west-comments-on-o_n_316476.html|title=Cornel West Comments on Obama's Nobel Peace Prize: Hard to Be War President with Peace Prize|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=October 10, 2009|accessdate=October 28, 2009 }}</ref><ref>Schneider, Matt. [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/wild-shoutfest-between-al-sharpton-and-cornel-west-on-obamas-leadership-on-racial-issues/ \"Wild Shoutfest Between Al Sharpton And Cornel West On Obama And Race\"]. mediaite.com. April 11, 2011. Retrieved 2011-4-11.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truthdig.com/report/item/the_obama_deception_why_cornel_west_went_ballistic_20110516 |title=Chris Hedges: The Obama Deception: Why Cornel West Went Ballistic \u2013 Chris Hedges |publisher=Truthdig.com |accessdate=2015-04-23}}</ref> In November 2012, West said in an interview that he considered Obama a \"[[Rockefeller Republican]] in [[blackface]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/cornel-west-obama-a-republican-in-blackface-black-msnbc-hosts-are-selling-their-souls/|title=Cornel West: Obama A 'Republican In Blackface,' Black MSNBC Hosts Are 'Selling Their Souls'|last=Kirell|first=Andrew|date=November 12, 2012|work=[[Mediaite]]|accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2012/11/30/an-interview-with-cornel-west-on-occupy-obama-and-marx/|title=An Interview with Cornel West on Occupy, Obama and Marx|work=[[CounterPunch]]|date=November 30, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, West participated in a \"Poverty Tour\" with [[Tavis Smiley]], his co-host on the [[Public Radio International]] program ''Smiley & West''. The tour became a two-part special on their radio program as well as a five-night special on the PBS television program ''Tavis Smiley''. They recounted their experience on the tour in their 2012 bestselling book ''The Rich and the Rest of Us''. The stated aim of the tour was to highlight the plight of the [[poverty in the United States|impoverished population of the United States]] prior to the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 presidential election]], whose candidates West and Smiley stated had ignored the plight of the poor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2011/8/9/cornel_west_tavis_smiley_on_obama|title=Cornel West & Tavis Smiley on Obama: 'Many of Us Are Exploring Other Possibilities in Coming Election'|publisher=Democracy Now!|date=August 9, 2011|accessdate=April 21, 2012}}</ref>[[File:Cornel West Introduces Bernie Sanders in South Carolina.webm|thumb|West introduces [[Bernie Sanders]] at a September 2015 [[Bernie Sanders presidential campaign, 2016|campaign]] rally in South Carolina]]In 2013, West referred to Obama's speech at the 50th anniversary celebration of [[Martin Luther King Jr.]]'s \"[[I Have a Dream]]\" speech as contradictory and as \"pretty words that hide ugly deeds.\" West then goes on to state, \"Martin Luther King Jr. had a dream. Barack Obama's got drones. Martin Luther King Jr. had prophetic missions. Barack Obama's got deadly missiles that he\u2019s ready to use.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/melanie-hunter/cornel-west-mlk-had-dream-barack-obama-s-got-drones|title=Cornel West: MLK Had a Dream; 'Barack Obama's Got Drones'|author=|date=September 5, 2013|website=CNS News|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, West gave an interview slamming Obama, calling him a \"counterfeit\" who posed as a progressive. West defined Obama's presidency as \"a Wall Street presidency, a drone presidency, a national security presidency.\"<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]|title=Cornel West: \"He posed as a progressive and turned out to be counterfeit. We ended up with a Wall Street presidency, a drone presidency\"|date=August 24, 2014|author= Thomas Frank |url= http://www.salon.com/2014/08/24/cornel_west_he_posed_as_a_progressive_and_turned_out_to_be_counterfeit_we_ended_up_with_a_wall_street_presidency_a_drone_presidency/|accessdate=2014-08-31}}</ref>\n\n=== 2016 presidential election ===\nIn 2015, West expressed his support for Democratic contender [[Bernie Sanders]] during an interview on ''CNN Tonight''. West argued that Sanders' plans to divert wealth from Wall Street elites to the poorest members of society would be beneficial for the African-American community.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ringoffireradio.com/2015/08/civil-rights-activist-cornel-west-throws-support-behind-bernie-sanders/|title=Civil Rights Activist Cornel West Throws Support Behind Bernie Sanders|publisher=Ring of Fire|date=August 19, 2015|accessdate=August 19, 2015}}</ref> On August 24, 2015, West tweeted, \"I endorse Brother @BernieSanders because he is a long-distance runner with integrity in the struggle for justice for over 50 years.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/08/25/bernie-sanders-gets-stamp-of-approval-from-cornel-west/?_r=0 Bernie Sanders Gets Stamp of Approval From Cornel West]. ''The New York Times.'' August 25, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, after Sanders exited the presidential race, West endorsed [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]] nominee [[Jill Stein]] and her running mate [[Ajamu Baraka]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/287829-sanders-ally-cornel-west-backs-green-candidate |title=Sanders ally Cornel West backs Green candidate |first=Mark |last=Hensch |date=July 14, 2016 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |accessdate=July 15, 2016 }}</ref> West, who is critical of the current US [[interventionism (politics)|interventionist]] foreign policy, referred to Democratic nominee [[Hillary Clinton]] as a \"[[neoliberal]] disaster\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2016/7/18/why_a_member_of_the_democratic|title=Cornel West: Why I Endorse Green Party's Jill Stein Over \"Neoliberal Disaster\" Hillary Clinton|author=|date=|website=democracynow.org|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref> and accused Clinton of merely posing as a [[progressivism in the United States|progressive]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2016/3/9/bernie_or_hillary_cornel_west_dolores|title=Bernie or Hillary? Cornel West & Dolores Huerta Debate After Sanders' Upset Win in Michigan|author=|date=|website=democracynow.org|accessdate=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the victory of [[Donald Trump]], West contended in an op-ed for ''[[The Guardian]]'' that white working- and middle-class voters \"rejected the economic neglect of [[neoliberal]] policies and the self-righteous arrogance of elites\", yet \"supported a candidate who appeared to blame their social misery on minorities, and who alienated Mexican immigrants, Muslims, black people, Jews, gay people, women and China in the process.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/nov/17/american-neoliberalism-cornel-west-2016-election Goodbye, American neoliberalism. A new era is here]. ''The Guardian.'' 17 November 2016.</ref>\n\n=== 2020 presidential election ===\nWest once again put his support behind [[Bernie Sanders]]' [[Bernie Sanders 2020 presidential campaign|2020 campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2019/03/07/cornel-west-on-bernie-trump-and-racism/|title=Deconstructed Podcast: Cornel West on Bernie, Trump, and Racism|last=Deconstructed|date=2019-03-07|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-28}}</ref>\n\n== Published works ==\n* \"Black Theology and Marxist Thought\" (1979) \u2013 essay\n* ''Prophesy Deliverance! An Afro-American Revolutionary Christianity'' (1982)\n* ''Post-Analytic Philosophy'', edited with John Rajchman (1985)\n* ''Prophetic Fragments'' (1988)\n* ''The American Evasion of Philosophy: A Genealogy of Pragmatism'' (1989)\n* ''Breaking Bread: Insurgent Black Intellectual Life'' (with [[bell hooks]], 1991)\n* ''The Ethical Dimensions of Marxist Thought'' (1991)\n* ''Prophetic Thought in Postmodern Times: Beyond Eurocentrism and Multiculturalism'' (1993)\n* ''[[Race Matters]]'' (1993)\n* ''Keeping Faith: Philosophy and Race in America'' (1994)\n* ''Jews and Blacks: A Dialogue on Race, Religion, and Culture in America'' (with [[rabbi]] [[Michael Lerner (rabbi)|Michael Lerner]], 1995)\n* ''[[The Future of the Race]]'' (with [[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]], 1996)\n* ''Restoring Hope: Conversations on the Future of Black America'' (1997)\n* ''The War Against Parents: What We Can Do for America's Beleaguered Moms and Dads'' (with [[Sylvia Ann Hewlett]], 1998)\n* ''The Future of American Progressivism'' (with [[Roberto Unger]], 1998)\n* ''The African-American Century: How Black Americans Have Shaped Our Century'' (with [[Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]], 2000)\n* ''Democracy Matters: Winning the Fight Against Imperialism'' (2004)\n* Commentary on ''[[The Matrix]]'', ''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' and ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]''; see ''[[The Ultimate Matrix Collection]]'' (with [[Ken Wilber]], 2004)\n* ''Hope on a Tightrope: Words & Wisdom'' (2008)\n* ''Brother West: Living & Loving Out Loud'' (2009)\n* ''[[The Rich and the Rest of Us: A Poverty Manifesto]]'' (with [[Tavis Smiley]], 2012)\n* ''Pro+Agonist: The Art of Opposition'' (2012)\n* ''Black Prophetic Fire'' (2014)\n\n==Filmography==\n;Film\n*''[[The Matrix Reloaded]]'' (2003) as Councilor West\n*''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'' (2003) as Councilor West\n*''[[Street Fight (film)|Street Fight]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Examined Life]]'' (2008)\n*''[[The Private Lives of Pippa Lee ]]'' (2009) as Don Sexton\n*''[[Bars4justice|#Bars4Justice]]'' (2015) as himself\n*''[[Chasing Trane: The John Coltrane Documentary ]]'' (2016) as himself\n*''[[No Safe Spaces]]'' (2019) as himself.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nationalreview.com/2019/11/documentary-no-safe-spaces-adam-carolla-dennis-prager-fight-free-speech-bans/ |title = In No Safe Spaces, an Odd Couple Teams up to Fight Free-Speech Bans|date = November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n;Television\n*\"[[What Will Happen to the Gang Next Year?]]\" (2012)\n\n==Discography==\n;Albums\n*''Sketches of My Culture'' (2001)\n*''Street Knowledge'' (2004)\n*''Never Forget: A Journey of Revelations'' (2007) <small>(with BMWMB)</small>\n\n;Guest appearances\n*[[E-40]] \u2013 \"Born in the Struggle\" from ''[[Revenue Retrievin': Overtime Shift]]'' (2011)\n*[[Bootsy Collins]] \u2013 \"Freedumb\" from ''[[Tha Funk Capital of the World]]'' (2011)\n*[[Immortal Technique]] \u2013 \"Sign of the Times\" from ''[[The Martyr (album)|The Martyr]]'' (2011)\n*[[Brother Ali]] \u2013 \"Letter to My Countrymen\" from ''[[Mourning in America and Dreaming in Color]]'' (2012)\n*[[Terence Blanchard]] \u2013 ''[[Choices (Terence Blanchard album)|Choices]]'' (2009)\n*[[Terence Blanchard]] \u2013 ''[[Breathless (Terence Blanchard album)|Breathless]]'' (2015)\n*[[Terence Blanchard]] \u2013 ''[[Live (Terence Blanchard album)|Live]]'' (2018)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Biography}}\n* [[Africana philosophy]]\n* [[American philosophy]]\n* [[Black existentialism]]\n* [[Christian left]]\n* [[List of American philosophers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/121550/cornel-wests-rise-fall-our-most-exciting-black-scholar-ghost |title=The Ghost of Cornel West |first=Michael Eric |last=Dyson |authorlink=Michael Eric Dyson |date=April 19, 2015 |journal=[[The New Republic]] }}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*{{IMDb name|0922002}}\n*{{Discogs artist|Cornel West}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Cornel West}}\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/cornel-west Column archive] at ''[[The Huffington Post]]''\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Alphonse Fletcher University Professor|years=1998\u20132002}}\n{{s-af