{"title_page": "King Richard II (1954 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1954 American TV film}}\n{{italictitle}}\n'''''King Richard II''''' is a 1954 American film directed by [[George Schaefer (director)|George Schaefer]] for the ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame|Hallmark Television Playhouse]]'' TV series.  It starred actor [[Maurice Evans (actor)|Maurice Evans]], who also adopted the [[screenplay|teleplay]] from the original work by [[William Shakespeare]].\n\n==Cast==\n*Maurice Evans as Richard II\n*[[Kent Smith]] as Bolingbroke\n*[[Frederick Worlock]] as John of Gaunt\n*[[Bruce Gordon (actor)|Bruce Gordon]] as Thomas Mowbray \n*Richard Purdy as Duke of York\n*[[Louis Hector]] as Henry Percy\n\n==Production==\nThe film was produced by [[Albert McCleery]] and directed by Schaefer.<ref>SCHAEFER--Problems In Directing: Effect Risks; By J.P. Shanley; New York Times; October 13, 1957: 135.</ref>  Production and art design was overseen by [[Richard Sylbert]].  Costumer design was by [[Noel Taylor (costume designer)|Noel Taylor]].\n\nThe screenplay was adapted by actor Evans from the [[Richard II (play)|play]] by Shakespeare.  Evans had performed Richard II on stage numerous times before. He had made his Shakespearean debut on TV in a 1953 Hallmark production of ''Hamlet''.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Shakespeare Through the Camera's Eye: ''Julius Caesar'' in Motion Pictures; ''Hamlet'' and ''Othello'' on Television |last = Griffin |first = Alice Venezky |journal = [[Shakespeare Quarterly]] |volume = 4 |issue = 3 |year = 1953 |pages = 331\u2013336 |doi = 10.2307/2866756 |jstor = 2866756 |ref = harv}}</ref>  ''King Richard II'' was sponsored by Hallmark for a reported $175,000.<ref name=\"new\"/><ref>Hallmark Hall of Fame, #3.18 (TV; 1954)</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe production was well received.<ref name=\"new\">Television Review: Evans' Richard II: 1 3/4-Hour Version of Stage Success Seen Over N. B. C. Stirring Performance of Star Overcomes Production Flaws\nBy Jack Gould. New York Times (1923-Current file); New York, N.Y. [New York, N.Y]; 25 Jan 1954: 25. </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0047409/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_105 ''King Richard II''] at [[IMDb]]\n{{George Schaefer}}\n{{Henriad}}\n[[Category:1954 in film]]\n\n{{tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1954 American TV film}}\n{{italictitle}}\n'''''King Richard II''''' is a 1954 American film directed by [[George Schaefer (director)|George Schaefer]] for the ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame|Hallmark Television Playhouse]]'' TV series.  It starred actor [[Maurice Evans (actor)|Maurice Evans]], who also adopted the [[screenplay|teleplay]] from the original work by [[William Shakespeare]].\n\n==Cast==\n*Maurice Evans, as Richard II\n*[[Kent Smith]] as Bolingbroke\n*[[Frederick Worlock]] as John of Gaunt\n*[[Bruce Gordon (actor)|Bruce Gordon]] as Thomas Mowbray \n*Richard Purdy as Duke of York\n*[[Louis Hector]], as Henry Percy\n\n==Production==\nThe film was produced by [[Albert McCleery]] and directed by Schaefer.<ref>SCHAEFER--Problems In Directing: Effect Risks; By J.P. Shanley; New York Times; October 13, 1957: 135.</ref>  Production and art design was overseen by [[Richard Sylbert]].  Costumer design was by [[Noel Taylor (costume designer)|Noel Taylor]].\n\nThe screenplay was adapted by actor Evans from the [[Richard II (play)|play]] by Shakespeare.  Evans had performed Richard II on stage numerous times before. He had made his Shakespearean debut on TV in a 1953 Hallmark production of ''Hamlet''.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Shakespeare Through the Camera's Eye: ''Julius Caesar'' in Motion Pictures; ''Hamlet'' and ''Othello'' on Television |last = Griffin |first = Alice Venezky |journal = [[Shakespeare Quarterly]] |volume = 4 |issue = 3 |year = 1953 |pages = 331\u2013336 |doi = 10.2307/2866756 |jstor = 2866756 |ref = harv}}</ref>  ''King Richard II'' was sponsored by Hallmark for a reported $175,000.<ref name=\"new\"/><ref>Hallmark Hall of Fame, #3.18 (TV; 1954)</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe production was well received.<ref name=\"new\">Television Review: Evans' Richard II: 1 3/4-Hour Version of Stage Success Seen Over N. B. C. Stirring Performance of Star Overcomes Production Flaws\nBy Jack Gould. New York Times (1923-Current file); New York, N.Y. [New York, N.Y]; 25 Jan 1954: 25. </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0047409/?ref_=nm_flmg_dr_105 ''King Richard II''] at [[IMDb]]\n{{George Schaefer}}\n{{Henriad}}\n[[Category:1954 in film]]\n\n{{tv-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nicholas0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast:no comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King_Richard_II_(1954_film)"}
{"title_page": "Carrollton, Missouri", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Carrollton, Missouri\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Aerial view of Carrollton, Missouri - 9-2-2013.JPG\n|imagesize                = 250px\n|image_caption            = Aerial view of Carrollton, Missouri\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Carroll_County_Missouri_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Carrollton_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = Location of Carrollton, Missouri\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Missouri]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Missouri|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Carroll County, Missouri|Carroll]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = [[Mayor-council]]\n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Scott Bartlett\n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name =\"Gazetteer files\"/>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 10.85\n|area_land_km2            = 10.80\n|area_water_km2           = 0.05\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 4.19\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 4.17\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.02\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 3509\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-07-08}}</ref>\n|population_total         = 3784\n|population_density_km2   = auto\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 230\n|elevation_ft             = 755\n|coordinates              = {{coord|39|21|32|N|93|29|44|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 64633\n|area_code                = [[Area code 660|660]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 29-11566<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web |url=http://factfinder2.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2008-01-31 |title=American FactFinder |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130911234518/http://factfinder2.census.gov/ |archivedate=2013-09-11 }}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0715434<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=2007-10-25}}</ref>\n|website                  =  [http://carrolltonareachamber.org/ Carrollton Area Chamber of Commerce]\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n\n'''Carrollton''' is a city in [[Carroll County, Missouri|Carroll County]], [[Missouri]], United States. Carrollton won the 2005 [[All-America City Award]], given out annually by the [[National Civic League]]. The population was 3,784 at the 2010 census. The population is down 338 residents since 2000. Carrollton is the [[county seat]] of Carroll County.<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2011-05-31 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nCarrollton was established in 1833.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shsmo.org/manuscripts/ramsay/ramsay_carroll.html |title=Carroll County Place Names, 1928\u20131945 (archived) |publisher=The State Historical Society of Missouri |accessdate=10 September 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624070725/http://shsmo.org/manuscripts/ramsay/ramsay_carroll.html |archivedate=24 June 2016 }}</ref>  It obtained its post office in 1834.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xcxWsmxRzVEC&lpg=PP3&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Missouri Roadsides: The Traveler's Companion | publisher=University of Missouri Press | author=Earngey, Bill | year=1995 | pages=38}}</ref>  Carrollton's growth can be documented through [[Sanborn Maps]], several of which are available online.<ref>[http://digital.library.umsystem.edu/image/umcscsanic/title/carrollton+missouri Sanborn Maps for Missouri: Carrollton], [[University of Missouri]] Digital Library.  Accessed 2011-03-14</ref>\n\nThe [[Carroll County Court House (Carrollton, Missouri)|Carroll County Court House]], [[Carroll County Sheriff's Quarters and Jail]], [[United States Post Office (Carrollton, Missouri)|United States Post Office]], and [[Wilcoxson and Company Bank]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCarrollton is located at {{coord|39|22|N|93|30|W|type:city}} (39.3589, -93.4956).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>  According to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|4.19|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|4.17|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.02|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web |title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2012-07-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=2012-07-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1860= 738\n|1870= 1832\n|1880= 2313\n|1890= 3878\n|1900= 3854\n|1910= 3452\n|1920= 3218\n|1930= 4058\n|1940= 4070\n|1950= 4380\n|1960= 4554\n|1970= 4847\n|1980= 4700\n|1990= 4406\n|2000= 4122\n|2010= 3784\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=3509\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Education==\nCarrollton R-VII School District operates Carrollton Area Career Center, Carrollton High School; grades 9-12, Carrollton Junior High School; grades 7\u20138, Carrollton Elementary School; grades 2\u20136, and Adams School; grades Pre-K-1.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.trojans.k12.mo.us/schools | title=Schools | publisher=Carrollton R-VII School District | accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe town has a lending library, the Carrollton Public Library.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.publiclibraries.com/missouri.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170610012728/http://www.publiclibraries.com/missouri.htm | url-status=dead | archive-date=10 June 2017 | title=Missouri Public Libraries | publisher=PublicLibraries.com | accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Carroll-ch.jpg|thumb|right|Carroll County Courthouse]]\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Thomas Archibald]], Colonel, US Army, Vietnam Veteran. 1958\u20131980. University Vice President, 1980\u20132002.\n* [[Amanda Austin]], painter and sculptor<ref name=\"Tufts(U.S.)1987\">{{cite book|author1=[[Eleanor Tufts]]|author2=National Museum of Women in the Arts (U.S.)|author3=International Exhibitions Foundation|title=American women artists, 1830\u20131930|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EvxPAAAAMAAJ|year=1987|publisher=International Exhibitions Foundation for the National Museum of Women in the Arts|isbn=978-0-940979-01-7}}</ref>\n* [[Leon E. Bates]], [[United Auto Workers|UAW]] leader\n* [[James Boyce (Louisiana politician)|James H. Boyce]], chairman of the [[Louisiana Republican Party]] from 1972 to 1976; born in Carrollton in 1922, died in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]], 1990\n* [[James Johnson Duderstadt]], President of the University of Michigan. 1988-1996\n* [[James Fergason]], graduated Carrollton High School in 1952. American inventor and business entrepreneur. A member of the National Inventors Hall of Fame. Best known for his work on an improved Liquid Crystal Display, or LCD. He held over one hundred U.S. patents at the time of his death.\n* [[Francis Doyle Gleeson]], Roman Catholic bishop\n* [[Don Martin (American football)|Don Martin]], defensive back for [[Yale University|Yale]]. Played in the [[National Football League|NFL]] for the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers|Buccaneers]], [[Kansas City Chiefs|Chiefs]], and [[New England Patriots|Patriots]], and coached in the NFL for the [[Oakland Raiders]].\n* [[John C. McQueen]], Major general, USMC; Decorated veteran of [[World War II]], involved in the construction of [[Camp Lejeune]] and [[Camp Pendleton]].\n* [[James Shields (politician, born 1810)|James Shields]], Civil War general and United States Senator\n* [[Robert Simpson (athlete)|Robert Simpson]], Robert Ingalls \"Bob\" Simpson was an American hurdler and track and field coach. Simpson set several world records in the 120 yd hurdles, equaled the world record in the 220 yd hurdles, and won two gold medals at the 1919 Inter-Allied Games. Simpson grew up on his family's farm in [[Bosworth, Missouri|Bosworth]], near Carrollton. He was the oldest of three brothers and part of a track and field family. Simpson's younger brothers John and [[Chauncey Simpson|Chauncey]] followed him in the sport, as did their cousin, William Sylvester.\n* [[Claude T. Smith]], American band conductor, composer, and educator.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110725141633/http://carrolltonareachamber.org/ Carrollton Area Chamber of Commerce]\n* Historic maps of Carrollton in the [http://dl.mospace.umsystem.edu/mu/islandora/object/mu%3A138743 Sanborn Maps of Missouri Collection] at the [[University of Missouri]]\n\n{{Carroll County, Missouri}}\n{{Missouri county seats}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Carroll County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:County seats in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Cities in Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Carrollton, Missouri\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Aerial view of Carrollton, Missouri - 9-2-2013.JPG\n|imagesize                = 250px\n|image_caption            = Aerial view of Carrollton, Missouri\n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Carroll_County_Missouri_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Carrollton_Hi