at light requirements of ''Tilia platyphyllos'' are greater than of ''Tilia cordata'' and that they change with climate, age of the tree and soil quality: [http://www.waldwissen.net/wald/naturschutz/arten/wsl_seba/wsl_seba_linden.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505053923/http://www.waldwissen.net/wald/naturschutz/arten/wsl_seba/wsl_seba_linden.pdf |date=2014-05-05 }} [http://www.wald-in-not.de/download13/linde.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031211153048/http://www.wald-in-not.de/download13/linde.pdf |date=2003-12-11 }}</ref>\n* ''[[Ulmus minor]]'', Field Elm\n\n'''Shade intolerant'''\n* ''[[Betula pendula]]'', Silver Birch, especially high light requirement\n* ''[[Betula pubescens]]'', Downy Birch\n* ''[[Juniperus communis]]'', Common Juniper\n* ''[[Larix decidua]]'', European Larch, especially high light requirement\n* ''[[Malus sylvestris]]'', European Crab Apple\n* ''[[Pinus mugo]]'', Mountain Pine\n* ''[[Pinus nigra]]'', European Black Pine\n* ''[[Pinus sylvestris]]'', Scots Pine\n* ''[[Populus alba]]'', Silver Poplar\n* ''[[Populus nigra]]'', Black Poplar\n* ''[[Populus tremula]]'', Aspen\n* ''[[Quercus pubescens]]'', Downy Oak\n* ''[[Quercus robur]]'', Pedunculate Oak\n* ''[[Salix alba]]'', White Willow\n* ''[[Salix caprea]]'', Goat Willow\n* ''[[Salix fragilis]]'', Crack Willow\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Trees}}\n*[http://forest.wisc.edu/sites/default/files/pdfs/publications/79.pdf Tolerance of Tree Species]\n*[http://www.na.fs.fed.us/spfo/pubs/silvics_manual/table_of_contents.htm Silvics of North America], an encyclopedia of characteristics for around 200 tree species native to the United States  published by the [[United States Forest Service]].\n*[http://www.utb-shop.de/downloads/dl/file/id/27/zusatzkapitel_zeigerwerte_der_pflanzen_mitteleuropas.pdf Zeigerwerte der Pflanzen Mitteleuropas (German)]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Tree Species By Shade Tolerance}}\n[[Category:Trees]]\n[[Category:Lists of trees|Shade-tolerance]]\n[[Category:Forest ecology|Shade tolerance list]]\n[[Category:Ecology lists|Shade tolerance]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nA list of [[tree]] species, grouped generally by [[Ecozone|biogeographic realm]] and specifically by [[Ecozone#Bioregions|bioregions]], and [[shade tolerance]]. '''Shade-tolerant species''' are species that are able to thrive in the [[Shade (shadow)|shade]], and in the presence of natural competition by other plants. '''Shade-intolerant species''' require full [[sunlight]] and little or no competition. '''Intermediate shade-tolerant''' trees fall somewhere in between the two.\n{{Expand list|date=May 2009}}\n\n==[[Americas]]==\n===[[Nearctic ecozone]]===\n====Eastern North America====\n'''Shade tolerant'''\n* ''[[Abies balsamea]]'', Balsam Fir\n* ''[[Acer negundo]]'', Boxelder\n* ''[[Acer saccharum]]'', Sugar Maple\n* ''[[Aesculus|Aesculus spp.]]'', Buckeyes\n* ''[[Chamaecyparis thyoides]]'', Atlantic White Cypress or Atlantic White Cedar\n* ''[[Cornus florida]]'', Flowering Dogwood\n* ''[[Persimmon|Diospyros spp.]]'', Persimmon\n* ''[[Fagus grandifolia]]'', American Beech\n* ''[[Ilex opaca]]'', American Holly\n* ''[[Ostrya virginiana]]'', Eastern Hophornbeam\n* ''[[Picea glauca]]'', White Spruce\n* ''[[Picea mariana]]'', Black Spruce\n* ''[[Picea rubens]]'', Red Spruce\n* ''[[Tilia americana]]'', Basswood\n* ''[[Thuja occidentalis]]'', Northern White Cedar\n* ''[[Morus rubra]]'', Red Mulberry\n* ''[[Carpinus caroliniana]]'', American Hornbeam\n* ''[[Magnolia grandiflora]]'', Southern Magnolia\n* ''[[Tsuga canadensis]]'', Eastern Hemlock\n* ''[[Tupelo|Nyssa spp.]]'', Tupelos\n* ''[[Carya laciniosa]]'', Shellbark Hickory <ref>{{cite book|title=Best Management Practices - Agroforestry Series Volume 1: Woodlot Management|date=2007|publisher=Ontario Ministry of Agriculture, Food and Rural Affairs|location=Toronto, Ontario, Canada|page=15|edition=18E}}</ref>\n\n'''Intermediat