are sometimes regarded as shade-tolerant and sometimes as light-loving. Two German papers claim that light requirements of ''Tilia platyphyllos'' are greater than of ''Tilia cordata'' and that they change with climate, age of the tree and soil quality: [http://www.waldwissen.net/wald/naturschutz/arten/wsl_seba/wsl_seba_linden.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505053923/http://www.waldwissen.net/wald/naturschutz/arten/wsl_seba/wsl_seba_linden.pdf |date=2014-05-05 }} [http://www.wald-in-not.de/download13/linde.pdf] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031211153048/http://www.wald-in-not.de/download13/linde.pdf |date=2003-12-11 }}</ref>\n* ''[[Ulmus minor]]'', Field Elm\n\n'''Shade intolerant'''\n* ''[[Betula pendula]]'', Silver Birch, especially high light requirement\n* ''[[Betula pubescens]]'', Downy Birch\n* ''[[Juniperus communis]]'', Common Juniper\n* ''[[Larix decidua]]'', European Larch, especially high light requirement\n* ''[[Malus sylvestris]]'', European Crab Apple\n* ''[[Pinus mugo]]'', Mountain Pine\n* ''[[Pinus nigra]]'', European Black Pine\n* ''[[Pinus sylvestris]]'', Scots Pine\n* ''[[Populus alba]]'', Silver Poplar\n* ''[[Populus nigra]]'', Black Poplar\n* ''[[Populus tremula]]'', Aspen\n* ''[[Quercus pubescens]]'', Downy Oak\n* ''[[Quercus robur]]'', Pedunculate Oak\n* ''[[Salix alba]]'', White Willow\n* ''[[Salix caprea]]'', Goat Willow\n* ''[[Salix fragilis]]'', Crack Willow\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Trees}}\n*[http://forest.wisc.edu/sites/default/files/pdfs/publications/79.pdf Tolerance of Tree Species]\n*[http://www.na.fs.fed.us/spfo/pubs/silvics_manual/table_of_contents.htm Silvics of North America], an encyclopedia of characteristics for around 200 tree species native to the United States  published by the [[United States Forest Service]].\n*[http://www.utb-shop.de/downloads/dl/file/id/27/zusatzkapitel_zeigerwerte_der_pflanzen_mitteleuropas.pdf Zeigerwerte der Pflanzen Mitteleuropas (German)]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Tree Species By Shade Tolerance}}\n[[Category:Trees]]\n[[Category:Lists of trees|Shade-tolerance]]\n[[Category:Forest ecology|Shade tolerance list]]\n[[Category:Ecology lists|Shade tolerance]]\n", "name_user": "104.207.9.208", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eWestern North America)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_tree_species_by_shade_tolerance"}
{"title_page": "2005 NCAA Division II football season", "text_new": "{{Infobox NCAA Division II season\n| year = 2005\n| image = 2005 Div2 Championship Logo.png\n| image_caption = The 2005 season's championship logo\n| regular_season = August 27 \u2013 November 5, 2005\n| playoffs = November 12 \u2013 December 10, 2005<ref>{{cite web|title=2000-2004 Grand Valley State Schedules|url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ii/gliac/grand_valley_state/2005-2009_yearly_results.php|work=College Football Warehouse|publisher=cfbdatawarehouse.com|accessdate=January 23, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111200502/http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ii/gliac/grand_valley_state/2005-2009_yearly_results.php|archive-date=January 11, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n| nc_date = December 10, 2005\n| championship = [[Braly Municipal Stadium]]<br>[[Florence, Alabama|Florence, AL]]\n| champion = [[Grand Valley State Lakers football|Grand Valley State]]\n| hill = [[Jimmy Terwilliger]], [[East Stroudsburg Warriors football|East Stroudsburg]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2005 NCAA Division II football season''', part of [[college football]] in the United States organized by the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] at the [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] level, began on August 27, 2005, and concluded with the [[NCAA Division II Football Championship]] on December 10, 2005 at [[Braly Municipal Stadium]] in [[Florence, Alabama]], hosted by the [[University of North Alabama]]. The [[Grand Valley State Lakers football|Grand Valley State Lakers]] defeated the [[Northwest Missouri State Bearcats football|Northwest Missouri State Bearcats]], 21\u201317, to win their third Division II national title.<ref>{{cite web|title=2005 NCAA Division II National Football Championship Bracket|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_champs_records/2012/d2/2012DIIfbchamp.pdf|work=NCAA|publisher=NCAA.org|accessdate=January 23, 2014|pages=14}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Harlon Hill Trophy]] was awarded to [[Jimmy Terwilliger]], quarterback from [[East Stroudsburg Warriors football|East Stroudsburg]].\n\n==Conference changes and new programs==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! School !! Former conference !! New conference\n|-\n| [[Central State University|Central State]] [[Central State Marauders|Marauders]] || ''New program'' || [[NCAA Division II independent schools|Independent]]\n|-\n| [[University of Charleston|Charleston]] [[Charleston Golden Eagles|Golden Eagles]] || [[NCAA Division II independent schools|Independent]] || [[West Virginia Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|WVIAC]]\n|-\n| [[Missouri University of Science and Technology|Missouri\u2013Rolla]] [[Missouri S&T Miners|Miners]] || [[Mid-America Intercollegiate Athletics Association|MIAA]] || [[NCAA Division II independent schools|Independent]]\n|-\n| [[Saint Paul's College (Virginia)|Saint Paul's]] [[Saint Paul's Tigers|Tigers]] || ''New program'' || [[Central Intercollegiate Athletic Association|CIAA]]\n|-\n| [[Stillman College|Stillman]] [[Stillman Tigers|Tigers]] || [[NCAA Division II independent schools|Independent]] || [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Conference|SIAC]]\n|}\n\n[[Stillman College|Stillman]] completed their transition to Division II and became eligible for the postseason.\n\n==Conference standings==\n\n===Northeast Region===\n{| cellpadding=\"5\"\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:30%;\"|{{2005 Northeast-10 Conference football standings | normal=1}}\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:30%;\"|{{2005 Pennsylvania State Athletic Conference football standings | normal=1}}\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:30%;\"|{{2005 West Virginia Intercollegiate Athletic Conference football standings | normal=1}}\n|}\n\n===Southeast Region===\n{| cellpadding=\"5\"\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:30%;\"|{{2005 Central Intercollegiate Athletic Association football standings | normal=1}}\n|  style=\"vertical-align:top; width:30%;\"|{{2005 Gulf South Conference football standin